Desi touch,"At least two Supreme Court judges, one of them the Chief Justice, have in recent months suggested “Indianisation” of the legal system. Chief Justice NV Ramana’s thought was limited to adapting the system to Indian “realities” and localising the justice delivery systems. Justice S Abdul Nazeer, however, wanted to “decolonise” the Indian legal system, emphasising that the ancient traditions of Manu, Kautilya or Yagnavalkya could not be neglected. He echoed former Chief Justice PN Bhagwati who once said our judicial thinking could not be “constricted” by reference to the law as it prevails in England. It is not the first such call. The Constituent Assembly debates touched upon this issue. In these times when nationalism is becoming almost a social grace, de-westernising Indian jurisprudence could as well be equated with a nationalist legal system. The history of India’s legal system is sufficiently ancient, dating back to the Vedic period or even earlier. The Mahabharata has references to the institution of Dharma. In the Vedic times, the objective of the law was to preserve Dharma that consisted of both legal and religious duties. Manu Smriti prescribes the rules and regulations for defending Dharma. The courts recognised three systems of law — Dharma Shastra, Arth Shastra and Sadachara or Charitra. The principles of jurisprudence were well-defined with grounds of litigation, jury systems, laws relating to witnesses, classification of “vivada” (disputes) and even judicial psychology. The legal tradition changed to one based around religious communities when the Mughals came in. While the Emperor’s law was all-powerful and the Sunni Hanafi tradition was the official legal system, the Shia and Hindu legal traditions were also recognised and practised. In the British period, the law evolved from religious prescription to the common law system. The British started coding the law and drafted the Indian Penal Code, the Code of Criminal Procedure and other statutes. When India became Independent, the Constitution steered Indian law away from colonial law to an organic one that has elements of secular law (once practised under the Mauryas) but predominantly rooting for social welfare to empower the weakest members of society. We need more clarity on what is meant by “Indianising” the legal system. It surely cannot be going back to the Vedic times. What exactly would we borrow from that period — the codification of law or the social ethos of that time that dictated the codification? For example, Indian law as we know it, does not, unlike the ancient law, distinguish between castes and communities. The current system stands for social justice and equality before law, not Brahminical interpretation of social code, rigid caste structures and patriarchy. Or, take the case of the Supreme Court judgment lifting the ban on entry of women of menstruating age into the Sabarimala temple. Would the ancient law have challenged a code backed by religion? A legal system can be tweaked but without diminishing its ability to serve justice in the times we live in.","Recently, Chief Justice NV Ramana and Justice S Abdul Nazeer of the Indian Supreme Court have advocated for the ""Indianisation"" of the legal system. Chief Justice Ramana emphasized adapting the system to Indian realities and localizing justice delivery, while Justice Nazeer called for decolonizing the legal system, suggesting that India's ancient legal traditions from figures like Manu and Kautilya should not be neglected. This echoes sentiments from former Chief Justice PN Bhagwati, who argued against constricting Indian judicial thinking to English law. India's legal history is ancient, with references to Dharma in the Mahabharata and laws from Vedic times focused on preserving Dharma through legal and religious duties. During the Mughal period, law varied by religious community, while British rule introduced a common law system and codified laws like the Indian Penal Code. Post-independence, the Indian Constitution shifted towards an organic legal system prioritizing social welfare and equality. The call for Indianising the legal system raises questions about its meaning. It cannot imply a return to Vedic-era laws, which distinguished between castes and communities, unlike contemporary Indian law which upholds social justice and equality. The Supreme Court's decision on the Sabarimala temple case, which lifted the ban on menstruating women, highlights the challenges of integrating ancient legal principles with modern justice. Any changes to the legal system must enhance its ability to serve contemporary justice without regressing to outdated social norms.",law,2021-12-31 00:00:00
Government aims to transform fair price shops into nutri-hubs,"The Indian government is set to transform around 100,000 fair price shops into ""nutri-hubs"" under the Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Anna Yojana (PMGKAY) over the next three years. These shops will sell nutritious items like millets, pulses, and dairy, along with subsidized grains. The initiative aims to generate additional income for shop owners and improve public nutrition. The government is collaborating with Sidbi and B2B platforms like Udaan to support these shops financially and operationally. This plan includes providing loans and credit facilities to shop owners, who will also sell FMCG products to boost their income. Additionally, these ""nutri-hubs"" aim to enhance the distribution and accessibility of nutritious products to a larger population. The Food Ministry has signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the National Institute for Entrepreneurship and Small Business Development to develop the entrepreneurship skills of ration dealers. A pilot program has been launched in states like Gujarat, Rajasthan, Telangana, and Uttar Pradesh, with selected fair price shops being converted into ""Jan Poshan Kendras"" (nutrition hubs). The initiative also includes operational reforms, such as integrating digital payment systems and other measures to streamline operations and improve efficiency at these outlets. The government hopes this transformation will help address nutritional challenges while increasing the economic viability of fair price shops.","The Indian government is planning to turn 100,000 fair price shops into ""nutri-hubs"" over the next three years as part of the Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Anna Yojana (PMGKAY). These revamped shops will sell nutritious items like millets, pulses, and dairy products alongside subsidized grains. The initiative aims to boost the income of shop owners while improving access to nutritious food for beneficiaries. Support will come from financial institut