Yoga School inaugurated at Sanchi Buddhist University,"The Yoga School set up by the students of Yoga Department of Sanchi Buddhist University was inaugurated on Thursday. The Yoga School is located at Sanchi Buddhist-Indian University of Knowledge Studies. The special thing about this yoga school is that it has been made from natural things. All the students of the Yoga Department built the terrace with the grass, the floor with cow dung and mud and preparing Buddhist platforms. The doors of the yoga school are made of bamboo and wood, the four walls of the campus with coconut rope and dates (chhind) leaves. The walls of the Buddhist Yoga Centre have been made with bullets and its roof is also made of grass. Do not disturb mosquito-fly during meditation and yoga activities. Assistant Professor of Yoga Department, Upendra Babu Khatri said that after the construction of this Yoga School, the students have prepared this action plan that they will go to every village to teach yoga to the villagers. According to Khatri, such efforts are made to create a laboratory with a natural environment with the least expense and natural resources. In this programme organised on the occasion of the death anniversary of Vasant Panchami and Gandhi, Assistant Professor of the Hindi Department, Rahul Siddharth explained how Vasant is mentioned in Hindi literature. He told that Hindi literature started from 1000 AD. Since then, the mention of spring has been found in Hindi literature. He said that in 16th century, the author of Padmavat, Malik Mohammad Jaisi also mentioned Vasant in his writing done in Awadhi. In the same way Bharatendu, Nazir Akbarabadi, Subhadra Kumari Chauhan, Sumitranandan Pant, Hazari Prasad Dwivedi and Vidya Niwas Mishra have mentioned Vasant in their poems. Assistant Professor of Yoga Department, Upendra Babu Khatri said that Gandhi used to do yoga as well. He said that Gandhi was believed in karma yoga. Khatri said that Acharya Shriram Sharma had gone to Mahatma Gandhi to learn yoga.","The Yoga School established by the students of the Yoga Department at Sanchi Buddhist-Indian University of Knowledge Studies was inaugurated on Thursday. Built using natural materials, the school features a grass terrace, a floor made of cow dung and mud, and Buddhist platforms. The doors are crafted from bamboo and wood, while the walls are constructed with coconut rope and chhind leaves. The roof is also made of grass, designed to keep out mosquitoes and flies during meditation and yoga. Assistant Professor Upendra Babu Khatri highlighted that the students plan to teach yoga in villages. This initiative aims to create a natural, low-cost laboratory environment. During the inauguration, Assistant Professor Rahul Siddharth discussed the significance of Vasant (spring) in Hindi literature, noting its mention from 1000 AD to contemporary poets. Additionally, Khatri mentioned Mahatma Gandhi’s practice of karma yoga and his influence on yoga teachings.",Education,2020-01-31 00:00:00
"Manipur: Advocate Seeks Immunity for Village Volunteers, Valley Organisations""","In Manipur, an advocate has called for legal immunity for village volunteers and valley organizations, arguing that their efforts are crucial for maintaining local security and social order. On November 30, 2023, the advocate presented a petition highlighting the vital role these groups play in supplementing the state's limited resources in conflict-prone and remote areas. The petition emphasized that these volunteers and organizations often face legal challenges and threats while performing their duties. By granting immunity, the advocate believes that these groups can operate more effectively without fear of legal repercussions, thereby enhancing community safety and cohesion. The move aims to recognize and formalize the contributions of local volunteers and organizations in maintaining peace and stability in Manipur.","In Manipur, an advocate has called for legal immunity for village volunteers and valley organizations, arguing that their efforts are crucial for maintaining local security and social order. On November 30, 2023, the advocate presented a petition highlighting the vital role these groups play in supplementing the state's limited resources in conflict-prone and remote areas. The petition emphasized that these volunteers and organizations often face legal challenges and threats while performing their duties. By granting immunity, the advocate believes that these groups can operate more effectively without fear of legal repercussions, thereby enhancing community safety and cohesion. The move aims to recognize and formalize the contributions of local volunteers and organizations in maintaining peace and stability in Manipur.",Crime and Justice,2023-12-04 00:00:00
