2024 a breakthrough year for science: A look at some intriguing discoveries,"As 2024 draws to a close, let's reflect on some of the most remarkable inventions and discoveries in science and technology. From groundbreaking medical breakthroughs and significant space exploration milestones to advances in ancient genetics, this year has been filled with exciting progress and innovations.HIV prevention drug Lenacapavir: Approved in 2022, Lenacapavir showed impressive results in 2024 trials with a 96% success rate in one and 100% in another. Administered as a semi-annual shot, it serves as an HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), according to Discover Magazine.Fruit fly brain mapping: In October 2024, scientists released a detailed map of 140,000 neurons in a fruit fly’s brain, helping to understand human cognition and memory. The research took 10 years to complete. New super-Earth discovery: NASA found TOI-715 b, a super-Earth 137 light-years away, in a habitable zone. It may support liquid water. A potential smaller Earth-like planet, TIC 271971130.02, could also exist in its orbit. Neanderthal and human interbreeding: Recent studies pinpoint the timeline of interbreeding between humans and Neanderthals, based on genetic data. Researchers analysed 59 ancient human genomes and 275 modern human genomes to determine when Neanderthals and humans coexisted in Eurasia. Their findings show that the two species lived together for about 7,000 years, from 50,500 to 43,500 years ago.","As 2024 ends, we reflect on some remarkable advancements in science and technology. In healthcare, the HIV prevention drug Lenacapavir demonstrated a 96% to 100% success rate in trials, offering a semi-annual shot as a pre-exposure prophylaxis. In neuroscience, a detailed map of 140,000 neurons in a fruit fly’s brain was released, advancing our understanding of human cognition and memory after a decade of research. In space exploration, NASA discovered TOI-715 b, a super-Earth in a habitable zone 137 light-years away, which may support liquid water. Genetic studies revealed that humans and Neanderthals interbred for about 7,000 years, between 50,500 and 43,500 years ago, based on analyses of ancient and modern genomes.",Science and Technology,2024-12-31 00:00:00
