ion mark on his election to the Lok Sabha.” “I demand that he be removed from the Cabinet,” Dr. Joshi said. Sources in the BJP suggest that Mr. Chidambaram is being targeted because of Hindutva terror cases against some RSS ‘pracharaks.' Some senior leaders have been trying to assuage RSS fears by telling them they are speaking to Mr. Chidambaram to “sort out the issue.” But the fear is that nothing concrete has happened to let the RSS completely off the hook on these cases. Dr. Joshi did not spare Manmohan Singh either, saying “as always, the Prime Minister keeps all such issues at arm's length.” He dismissed questions on the propriety of his using the BJP office to address issues related to the PAC's work.","Public Accounts Committee Chairman, Murli Manohar Joshi, demanded the removal of Union Home Minister P. Chidambaram from the Cabinet over his alleged role in the 2G spectrum allocation case and the gas scandal involving Reliance Industries Limited. Joshi cited the draft report of the Comptroller and Auditor-General (CAG) and called for an inquiry into the leak, stating it was a ""matter of privilege."" He questioned the delay in the Ministry's response to the CAG's draft report and criticized Chidambaram for allowing private gas companies to increase the gas price, causing a significant loss to the exchequer.",National News,2011-06-17 00:00:00
State gaols turn death traps for prisoners,"State gaols turn death traps for prisoners HYDERABAD: The death of 104 prisoners while incarcerated, made theprisons in Andhra Pradesha scary place in 2009-10.C N Gopinath Reddy, prisons department director general of police said the number of death of prisoners was high. The deaths could be attributed to a lack of doctors in jails, indifference at government hospitals to prisoners and a shortage of police escorts.On arrival, every new inmate undergoes a medical checkup, but may not always receive prompt medical attention as required.Of the 104 prisoners who died in the last year, 96 were in government hospitals, while others were in the prisons themselves. In a state known for its prison department reforms, the statistics are even more spine-chilling.In fact, Andhra Pradesh has been occupying the third place in terms of the number of deaths in prisons in recent years.The National Human Rights Commission (HHRC) has pointed out that out of the 1527 deaths during 2008-09 in prisons in the country, 287 were in Uttar Pradesh, 133 in Bihar and 131 in Andhra Pradesh.The latest National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB) report of Prison Statistics for the year 2008 said there were 1449 prison deaths. This includes, 295 in Uttar Pradesh, 144 in Bihar and 127 in Andhra Pradesh. Similarly for the year 2007, out of the total 1423 deaths in prisons, 180 were in Uttar Pradesh, 164 in Bihar and 117 in Andhra Pradesh.One of the biggest problems that jails in the state have been facing is an insufficiency of police escorts. Without the escorts, prisoners cannot be taken to government hospitals for checkups and treatment. Although this was taken up with the police department which provides escorts, the problem has not been addressed. For this reason, some prisoners who do require treatment cannot be taken to hospital.Sources have said that when prisoners exhibit no signs of serious illness, prison doctors do not take much interest and do not perform a thorough examination. In February 2008, Krishna, an undertrial facing murder charges at Chanchalguda jail, suddenly developed chest pain but did not survive even the ride to the hospital.However, another problem that reportedly blights prisoners is the lack of care provided to them in government hospitals likeOsmania General Hospitaland Gandhi Hospital. In May last year, a 45-year-old undertrial prisoner lodged in the Cherlapally Central Prison complained of severe chest pain, and although he was rushed to Gandhi Hospital, he died the same night.Many of the prison deaths are also due to Aids. When prisoners with Aids are admitted to hospitals, they (the hospitals) tend to give up on the patients, especially if the disease has progressed.""When a convict or an undertrial comes to the jail, he may already have a serious ailment for which medical attention is given. But what is important for us to do now is to observe if anyone could be suffering a mental trauma and offer help so that it does not lead to serious ailments,"" Gopinath Reddy said. There are more than 140 jails across the state and 15,000 inmates, most of whom are undertrials.","State gaols turn death traps for prisoners HYDERABAD: The death of 104 prisoners while incarcerated, made theprisons in Andhra Pradesha scary place in 2009-10.C N Gopinath Reddy, prisons department director general of police said the number of death of prisoners was high.",Politics,2011-06-01 00:00:00
