Off-campus centre in UGC list of ‘illegals’ cleared ahead of Modi visit,"With Prime Minister Narendra Modi scheduled to inaugurate the permanent campus of the National Institute of Science Education and Research (NISER) in Bhubaneswar on February 7, the University Grants Commission (UGC) swung into action and granted approval to the institute Thursday. This development comes within three months of the higher education regulator directing the prestigious Homi Bhabha National Institute (HBNI) in Mumbai, along with nine other deemed universities, to shut down their off-campus centres on the ground that they were “unauthorised” and set up without UGC’s permission. The NISER, which is affiliated with HBNI, was among the off-campus centres put on notice. Apprised of Modi’s impending visit to the institute by the Prime Minister’s Office (PMO) three weeks ago, sources said, the UGC got cracking on NISER’s long-pending application and scheduled an inspection of its campus, faculty and facilities on January 25. The final approval came during the UGC meeting held Thursday afternoon.","The University Grants Commission (UGC) moved quickly to approve the National Institute of Science Education and Research (NISER) on Thursday, in anticipation of Prime Minister Narendra Modi's February 7 inauguration of the institute's permanent site in Bhubaneswar. This development occurs three months after the esteemed Homi Bhabha National Institute (HBNI) in Mumbai and nine other deemed universities were ordered by the higher education regulator to close their off-campus centers on the grounds that they were ""unauthorised"" and established without the UGC's approval. HBNI-affiliated NISER was one of the off-campus centers that was placed under notice. When the Prime Minister's Office (PMO) announced three weeks ago that Modi would be visiting the institute, according to sources, the UGC got serious.",Education,2016-02-05 00:00:00
