Divided opinion over uniform syllabus,"Chennai: ""Many universities are already borrowing material from IGNOU, so having a uniform syllabus may help. Confusion often arises due to different universities having their own eligibility rules and this will be removed with such a move,"" he said, adding that credibility of the courses is another matter entirely. Ravichandran said that distance learning has become increasingly popular globally and more universities offering such courses had been established over the years. A minimum of 40,000-45,000 enrolments take place every year with the university, he said. However, the number of graduates varies as some students take many years to complete a course. The Tamil Nadu Open University has approximately 30,000 students graduating every year and offers courses from more than 20 centres in the state. Vice Chancellor of TNOU, M Bhaskaran, said that bringing in uniformity would be very beneficial for students as it would put them on an equal footing, no matter which university they opt for. He also added that there has been a sustained interest, especially with many homemakers and employees taking up distance learning. However, some academicians were of the opinion that this may not be a healthy move as it threatens the autonomy of universities. ""The concept of uniform syllabus ends at the plus two level and doesn't extend to the university level at all. It affects the autonomy of the universities and institutions cannot make independent decisions on how they want to offer the course,"" said R Thilagaraj, a Madras University syndicate member formerly with TNOU.","The University Grants Commission (UGC) in India is considering introducing uniform syllabi for all universities offering distance education courses. Dr. A Gnanam, director of Madras University’s Institute of Distance Education, welcomed the idea, stating it would help eliminate confusion and simplify enrolment processes. However, some academics argue that uniform syllabi would infringe on university autonomy and limit institutions' ability to make independent decisions about course offerings.",Education,2016-08-10 00:00:00
Fake cheques eating into DVB’s revenues,"NEW DELHI: Touts are operating unabated at the local Delhi Vidyut Board (DVB) offices in connivance with the staff. Last year, DVB cashiers in collusion with touts credited bogus bank cheques worth Rs eight crore. These fake bank cheques were deposited by the consumers to settle electricity bills and various other dues. Due to such incidents, the DVB has been incurring a huge revenue loss. While early this year, the DVBâ€™s vigilance wing was able to recover Rs 1.5 crore through special raids at the district offices in the east circle, DVBâ€™s losses have been mounting. Officials say since January this year, DVB has received fake cheques worth Rs three crore. â€˜â€˜Not only does it mean revenue loss to the DVB. It also institutionalises corruption in the electricity board,â€™â€™ said a senior DVB official. According to S K Mittal, assistant engineer in the DVB vigilance wing, the consumers who owe huge amounts often approach touts who promise to get their dues reduced. The consumers usually pay these touts half the amount they owe to the DVB. The touts, in turn, submit bank cheques drawn on fake accounts to the agency. The DVB cashier at the counter credits these cheques immediately, issuing a receipt of payment to the consumer. â€˜â€˜Since the DVB credits the cheques immediately and does not wait for payment from the bank, we do not come to know about the authenticity of the cheques till they bounce,â€™â€™ Mittal said.To make investigation on the bounced cheques difficult, the DVB cashiers often put wrong consumer (or K) numbers on the cheques. â€˜â€˜We often find these bogus cheques with the K number of consumers who have either paid their dues or do not owe anything,â€™â€™ Mittal said. Acting on the bogus cheque racket, the DVBâ€™s vigilance wing started a special drive in January this year. Three cashiers were suspended and 20 touts were arrested. The 150 consumers who paid through bogus cheques were mostly big consumers.","Touts, in collusion with Delhi Vidyut Board (DVB) staff, are causing significant revenue losses through a bogus cheque scheme. Consumers, often large debtors, pay touts to reduce their dues, and these touts then deposit fake cheques which are promptly credited by DVB cashiers. This racket has led to losses of Rs eight crore last year and Rs three crore this year. The vigilance wing has initiated a special drive, suspending three cashiers and arresting 20 touts, while recovering Rs 1.5 crore through raids.",Crime and Justice,2002-05-22 00:00:00
Rupee Coop Bank's liquidity position comfortable: RBI,"the liquidity position of pune-based rupee co-operative bank ltd that was found to have flouted certain rbi norms ""continues to be comfortable and its overall financial health is not a cause of concern for depositors"", reserve bank of india said on friday. the deposits in the bank up to rs one lakh were fully insured under the insurance cover of deposit insurance and credit guarantee corporation, rbi spokesperson said in a release. on february 12, rupee bank was taken over by an administrator in view of the irregularities committed by the board of directors flouting the rbi norms to the detriment of the bank and against the interests of depositors. rbi spokesperson said the central bank was in close contact with the administrator and was fully supportive of the new management in ensuring full safety of depositors'' funds, sufficient liquidity and financial viability of the bank. rbi was in full agreement with the steps taken by the registrar of co-operative societies and maharashtra government to ensure efficient functioning of the bank in the interest of its depositors and members.","The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) stated that the liquidity position of Pune-based Rupee Co-operative Bank Ltd remains comfortable, and its overall financial health doesn't pose concerns for depositors. The bank's deposits up to Rs one lakh are fully insured under the Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation. On February 12, the bank was placed under an administrator due to irregularities committed by the board of directors, violating RBI norms and risking depositors' interests. The RBI assured its support to the new management in ensuring the safety of depositors' funds, adequate liquidity, and financial viability. It also backed the actions taken by the Registrar of Co-operative Societies and the Maharashtra government to facilitate the efficient functioning of the bank for the benefit of depositors and members.",Busine