"Bombay HC quashes rape FIR against builder, imposes Rs 50,000 cost","MUMBAI: The Bombay high court has quashed a rape FIR registered against a builder who had approached the court saying it was a consensual relationship and the victim had filed the complaint due to ""some confusion"" and now they have amicably settled the matter. The division bench of Justices Revati Mohite Dere and Prithviraj Chavan last week quashed the FIR lodged at NRI Coastal police station and directed the petitioner to deposit within three weeks, Rs 50,000 with Jeevan Sandhya Mangalya Sansthan as cost. The petitioner, who is a partner in a construction fi-rm, is married and has two so-ns. The victim, a former sales manager at his firm, is a divorcee with a five-year-old son. Police said the woman joined the firm in 2020 and got close to the builder. They started living together as he promised to divorce his wife and marry her. However, later he broke off the relationship and she lost her job. She said in January 2021, she re-established contact with the builder and he convinced her to get together again. When she got pregnant, he took her to a clinic in Seawoods and made her to undergo an abortion, she said. The woman said when she was unwell, she called him up, but his wife sent a text from his phone telling her not to contact him and blocked her number. She then filed a complaint and two months later, police filed a chargesheet in the rape case. Advocate Mahesh Vaswani, along with advocate Sheetal Patkar and Shreya Tiwari, led the arguments for the petitioner, while Dharini Nagda appeared for the complainant, who also gave her consent for quashing the FIR. ""Both parties have amicably settled the matter and have decided to quash the FIR. In the petition, the victim said she had lodged the complaint due to a misunderstanding and in the heat of the moment,"" said Vaswani. The victim told the court that the allegations in the FIR are purely of personal nature and she has no objection if the FIR and the chargesheet are quashed and set aside as they have amicably settled the dispute. The HC then quashed the FIR.","The Bombay High Court has quashed a rape FIR registered against a builder. The petitioner, a partner in a construction firm, argued that the relationship was consensual, and the victim filed the complaint due to “some confusion.” The court accepted their amicable settlement and directed the petitioner to deposit Rs 50,000 with Jeevan Sandhya Mangalya Sansthan as cost. The victim, a former sales manager at the firm, had re-established contact with the builder after a breakup. The chargesheet in the rape case was filed two months after her complaint. The High Court quashed the FIR after considering both parties’ consent and the personal nature of the allegations.",Crime and Justice,2024-01-13 00:00:00
