Tea prices drop on higher supply in South India,"Higher supply of tea has put pressure on the market with prices in South India declining by nearly R20 per kg year-on-year. Further, lower prices of tea in Kenya have limited Indian CTC tea exports, leading to a glut in the market, traders said. The situation is alarming for many plantations in South India, which are operating on wafer-thin margin due to higher input and social costs. The situation is grim and similar to the one faced during 2004-05. With adequate amount of tea in the market and lower exports, there seems to be no scope of improvement in price in the short-term,? Chacko P Thomas, managing director, Kanan Devan Hills Plantation (KDHP) told FE. He said most of the plantations are facing a very serious crisis with production looking good. Market prices have dropped to R40-50 per kg for lower grade CTC tea from R65-75 per kg a year ago, N Sriram of Contemporary Tea Auctioneers said. ?Whenever tea production in South India increases, it has put pressure on the market because most of the production is CTC. Higher production of CTC tea in Kenya lowers Indian exports .Orthodox tea is faring better when compared to CTC,? he added. Tea Board data shows that total tea production during 2014 for the January-August period is higher by 10.76 mkg in South India ,while North India stands lower by 17.98 mkg when compared to the corresponding period of 2013.","The tea market in South India is facing significant challenges as oversupply has driven prices down by approximately ₹20 per kilogram compared to the previous year. Traders attribute this decline to reduced Indian CTC tea exports, impacted by lower prices of tea from Kenya. The surplus in the market has created a difficult situation for plantations in South India, particularly affecting those operating with narrow profit margins due to rising input and social costs. Chacko P Thomas, managing director of Kanan Devan Hills Plantation (KDHP), described the crisis as severe, resembling conditions seen in 2004-05, with little prospect of short-term price improvement despite adequate production levels. Market reports indicate that prices for lower-grade CTC tea have fallen to ₹40-50 per kg from ₹65-75 per kg a year ago. N Sriram from Contemporary Tea Auctioneers highlighted that increased CTC tea production in South India exacerbates market pressures, while orthodox tea varieties fare comparatively better. According to Tea Board data, South India's tea production from January to August 2014 has risen by 10.76 million kilograms, contrasting with a decrease of 17.98 million kilograms in North India during the same period compared to 2013.",National News,2014-10-31 00:00:00
