Recently repaired Itanagar-Hollongi NH develops cracks,"A large portion of the Itanagar-Hollongi national highway (NH), which had been repaired just before the nationwide lockdown was imposed, has developed major cracks following sporadic rainfall in the past few weeks. This stretch of the highway had eroded a few months earlier and had been filled up by the Itanagar highway division, but it has developed cracks, making it dangerous for vehicles to ply on it. Speaking to this daily, Itanagar Highway Division Executive Engineer Nani Tath informed: “When the road was falling apart, a hill had to be cut down to fill it. We could not do anything to the hill as it requires natural settlement. We water it, so that settlement takes place, and then we go for casting, and the filling of the road was done without proper compaction due to the deep gorge.” The road “has now been left as it is intentionally for the rainwater to percolate down to create natural compaction and settlement, and a 30- to 40-metre side drain will be connected to it,” he said. Informing that repair work is likely to begin by Wednesday, the EE said “enough percolation must have taken place by now, and I have directed the contractor to connect the drain, so that the new work does not get affected.” Tath informed that the contractor is yet to get paid for all the work done so far, due to non-sanctioning of fund against the damages, but has assured to continue the work on request. “We have submitted the estimate to the ministry of road transport & highways, which is under consideration as the same was also inspected by union MoS for Road Transport & Highways, VK Singh, the last time he visited. “The minister had instructed the ministry’s regional officer that he would sanction the fund, and had asked us to go ahead with the work. We have carried out the work at his direction,” the EE said. Officials from the union road transport & highways ministry’s Itanagar regional office (Camp Tezpur) had inspected the damages on 2 August, 2019, and the minister had also seen the damages during his maiden visit to the state capital on 28 August, 2019.","Following sporadic rainfall, a repaired portion of the Itanagar-Hollongi national highway (NH) has developed major cracks, rendering it dangerous for vehicles. The repairs were done just before the nationwide lockdown, filling up an eroded stretch. However, the filling was done without proper compaction due to a deep gorge, leading to the current issue. The highway division executive engineer explained that the road was intentionally left for rainwater to aid natural settlement and compaction. Repair work, expected to commence soon, awaits fund sanctioning from the Ministry of Road Transport & Highways, as directed by Union MoS VK Singh during his visit",GOVERNMENT,2020-05-13 00:00:00
"Take Turkish bath to heal paralysis , obesity","Hyderabad: Whenever someone mentions Masjid Miyan Mishk, one is reminded of the Garam Hamam (hot bath) there. Many think it was razed, but the fact is that it exists in a better condition and can be used after minor repairs. The masjid was built by Miyan Mishk, a noble in the court of Sultan Abdullah Qutub Shah, seventh ruler of the Qutb Sahi dynasty in the 16th century. The Masjid stands on a corner of Purana Pul. Garam Hamam is located inside the Masjid, behind a small graveyard to the right side, where a family whose ancestors were brought from Delhi to manage the Hamam lives. Managing committee president Samad Warsi said the hot bath was in good condition. “We are maintaining it, but no one is able to manage it according to ancient methods,” he said. Garam Hamam, also known as “Turkish bath” is a therapeutic method of cleansing and relaxation using hot water and steam. Turkish baths followed a 3-step process. There’s a sauna and steam bath and then a full body wash, often finished with a massage. Sweating during the hot bath can have caloric burning equivalent to running. Although the Turkish bath employed the same kind of heating system as the earlier Roman one, it is different in many ways. The Turkish bath consists of three sections: the cool room, the tepidity room, and the hottest room. Garam Hamam here consists of five chambers. The first two chambers are for initial exercise and changing and there are three treatment rooms. The last chamber is the main chamber where a person is treated to hot and steam bath and massages. In a separate chamber, quintals of firewood burn to boil the water and create steam. There are 3 basins to store water. A man has to spend half an hour in the hottest chamber, depending on his body’s resistance. He then shifts to the tepidity room, which is less hot, and then to the cool room where his body temperature is maintained and gradually brought down to room temperature. Heat makes the blood flow better and can relax muscles. Adding Epsom salt to a hot tub can also reduce inflammation of joints caused by arthritis or other musculo-skeletal disorders. Also, the anti-inflammatory property of salt baths has a positive effect on those suffering from metabolic diseases such as Type II diabetes. Dr Anjum Sultana, a Unani doctor, says steam baths are useful in reducing sinus pain, nasal congestion and severe cough. Nasal congestion is caused because of inflammation in nasal airways and the vapour causes the blood vessels of the face and nose to move, hence nasal secretions relax and dilate. Hot water bath helps the body’s immune system fight viruses better. She said very hot water can make the skin more sensitive, but hot water baths with extracts like coconut oil, olive oil or lavender extract as well as oatmeal can hydrate the skin and heal dryness and sensitivity. She said one should take this kind of bath under an expert who monitors not only temperature of the chamber but also checks its impact on the body. It is useful in healing paralysis, obesity and bad cholesterol.",Sweating during hot bath can have caloric burning to that of running.,Weather,2019-01-14 00:00:00
"IPL fan clubs to pitch in for cleaner stadia, meet in Hyderabad","If you were moved by social media videos of Japanese football fans cleaning up stadiums after a match, something similar is all set to happen in India. By Dhritiman Ganguly HYDERABAD: If you were moved by social media videos of Japanese football fans cleaning up stadiums after a match, something similar is all set to happen in India. For the first time in the country, official fan clubs of IPL franchises are keeping their team loyalties aside and meeting at University of Hyderabad (UOH) on Sunday afternoon, just ahead of the IPL final, to sign a declaration to have cleaner sports stadiums across the country.They will also chalk out a long-term plan to ensure cleanliness at all sporting events in their cities. The two fan clubs that not part of this meeting are the Rajasthan Royals and Kings XI Punjab as they had other engagements. The clubs have been brought together by Bengaluru-based International Institute of Waste Management (IIWM) which wants the fans to begin the battle against waste from the IPL final.","The article highlights a significant initiative in India inspired by Japanese football fans' post-match stadium clean-ups. Fan clubs of various IPL franchises are convening at the University of Hyderabad to sign a declaration aimed at promoting cleaner sports stadiums nationwide. Organized by the International Institute of Waste Management (IIWM), this marks the first time IPL fan clubs are coming together to prioritize stadium cleanliness, with a focus on the upcoming IPL final and a long-term strategy for future sporting events. Notably, two franchises, Rajasthan Royals and Kings XI Punjab, are not participating due to prior commitments. This collaborative effort underscores a collective commitment to environmental responsibility within India's sports culture.",Sports,2019-05-12 00:00:00
"Apple's iMac 21.5"" and 27"" : It's a pleasure","The iMac is Apple’s line of “all-in-one” desktop computers where the entire unit essentially comprises a display with all computing components built into the rear of the monitor. The iMacs come in two screen sizes—21.5” and 27” (length of the screen along the diagonal)—and we’ve tested a demo unit of each size. Legend has it that Apple founder Steve Jobs wears only polo-neck sweaters because he believes that buttons are a design flaw. That philosophy is certainly incorporated in these machines as both of us were a bit puzzled while trying to turn the machines on, until we finally located the (non-protruding) power button at the bottom left corner of the machine’s rear. The bottom right side on the rear has four USB ports, a firewire port, a ‘display out’ port, an ethernet port and microphone and headphone jacks. We didn’t really end up using the last three since the iMacs have built-in Wifi, microphone and excellent stereo speakers. There’s a tiny webcam lens just above the screen and an optical drive and memory card reader on the right side. But the real stand-out features of these machines are the gorgeous LEDbacklit screens which produce far superior colours, contrasts and viewing angles to any monitors we’ve seen before. While the 21.5” version has an impressive 1920x1080 pixel resolution, it looks absolutely pedestrian when compared to the stunning 2560x1440 resolution of its big brother. In fact, the latter’s screen size and sharpness is almost a disadvantage since one often struggled to move the mouse cursor from one end of the screen to another in one single arm motion. The 27” edition was beset with display problems at the time of its launch in the US but the piece that we tested held up without a problem for the 2-month testing period. Although both machines come with 4GB of RAM with expansion slots for upto 16 GB, there are a couple of hardware mix and match options for each iMac. The entry level models run on Intel’s Core 2 Duo 3.06 GHz processors but the 27” version can be purchased with the powerful new Intel i7 quad-core processors, allowing it to be used for industrial level movie editing, for instance. One also has a choice of graphic cards and hard disk sizes (ranging from 500 MB to 2 TB) depending on usage needs. Both models run Apple’s latest operating system version 10.6, dubbed ‘Snow Leopard’, which is more of an upgrade to the ‘Tiger’ (10.5) version rather than an entirely new OS. The bundled wireless keyboard has lost all its weight and is razor thin. While it is sturdy, the keys are much smaller and are more suitable for typing rather than professional video editing. The one we got with the 27” version seemed to wobble a bit during high-speed typing. The new Magic Mouse, which has no buttons but mimmicks the gesture control found on all the new large touchpads of the MacBook laptops is a joy to work with, though it might require some getting used to sans scrolling and clicking. Starting at Rs 65,000 and Rs 90,000 respectively for the 21.5” and 27” models with the latter going up to well over a lakh for the souped-up configurations, the iMac is by no means an affordable computer. However, if price is no constraint, then there is probably no better desktop computer available in the market in terms of looks, design, specifications and the sheer joy of using a beautifully engineered machine.","The article provides an in-depth review of Apple's iMac desktop computers, covering both the 21.5-inch and 27-inch models. Key points: The iMac features an ""all-in-one"" design with the entire computing components integrated into the rear of the display. The standout feature is the stunning LED-backlit display, offering impressive resolutions of 1920x1080 (21.5-inch) and 2560x1440 (27-inch). The 27-inch model can be configured with powerful Intel i7 quad-core processors, making it suitable for professional tasks like video editing. Other hardware options include RAM, storage, and graphics card choices to suit different user needs. The wireless keyboard and Magic Mouse provide a clean, minimalist input experience, though the keyboard may not be ideal for intensive typing. Starting at Rs 65,000 and Rs 90,000 respectively, the iMac is a premium offering, but its excellent design, specifications, and user experience justify the high price for those who can afford it. The review highlights the iMac's standout features, design, and performance capabilities, making it a compelling desktop choice for those who value aesthetics and engineering excellence.",Technology and Gadgets,2010-02-25 00:00:00
BMW launches new X3 priced up to Rs49.9 lakh,"German luxury carmaker BMW on Thursday launched facelift of the second generation of the SUV X3 priced up to Rs49.9 lakh (ex-showroom Delhi). “In order to strengthen our presence in the country, we would aggressively expand our product range in the luxury segment,” said BMW Group India President Philipp von Sahr. “We would launch the M3 sedan, M4 Coupe, M5 sedan and hybrid car i8 in 2014 ,” he added. The new X3 is being locally produced at the company’s Chennai plant and is available only in diesel option. It goes on sale across the country from Thursday onwards. The new X3 will be available in two variants priced at Rs44.9 lakh and Rs49.9 lakh (ex-showroom). It is equipped with various luxury features, including the eight-speed automatic transmission with cruise control. The company had first launched the X3 model in 2003, followed by the second generation in 2011. The model launched on Thursday is the facelift of the second generation of the SUV.” The company also plans to expand dealer network in the country by 2015 end by taking the overall number to 50 from 37 currently. BMW India, which is wholly-owned subsidiary of the Germany’s BMW Group, currently produces various vehicles at its Chennai facility including the 1 Series, 3 Series, X1 and X3.","On Thursday, German luxury carmaker BMW launched the facelift of the second generation SUV X3 in India, priced up to Rs 49.9 lakh (ex-showroom Delhi). The new X3 is being locally produced at the company's Chennai plant and is available only in the diesel option. It is equipped with various luxury features, including the eight-speed automatic transmission with cruise control. BMW India also plans to expand its dealer network in the country by the end of 2015, increasing the overall number to 50 from 37 currently.",Automotive,2014-08-29 00:00:00
Alarming rise in unemployment rates in Asia and the Pacific,"As per the recent report of ILO Global Employment Trends for Youth 2022: Asia and the Pacific, the unemployment rate of young people aged between 15 and 24 years in Asia and the Pacific is estimated to have reached 14.9 per cent in 2022, which is the same as the global average. While that rate represents a decrease from the rate of the previous year (15.5 per cent), it remains higher than the pre-pandemic benchmark of 13.3 per cent in 2019. Beyond the regional aggregate, there are important divergences between sub-regions and countries in the evolution of unemployment rates and other labour market indicators. In both Southern and Eastern Asia, youth unemployment rates in 2022 are projected to be higher than the pre-pandemic benchmark by less than 1 percentage point, whereas in Southeast Asia and the Pacific, the corresponding rate is projected to be higher by 2 percentage points. In Sri Lanka, which is currently experiencing balance of payments and sovereign debt crises, youth unemployment in the second quarter of 2021 was at 30.0 per cent, whereas in Vietnam, which is benefiting from diversification strategies of global value chains as COVID-19 lockdowns in China persist, the corresponding rate for the same quarter was 5.5. per cent. Young men in the region face substantially higher unemployment rates (16.0 per cent) than young women (12.7 per cent). However, when examining a more comprehensive measure of labour underutilization, that is, the combined rate of youth unemployment and potential labour force (termed the LU3 rate), the gap between men and women diminishes, pointing to young women having higher potential labour force rates than young men.","As per the recent report of ILO Global Employment Trends for Youth 2022: Asia and the Pacific, the unemployment rate of young people aged between 15 and 24 years in Asia and the Pacific is estimated to have reached 14.9 per cent in 2022, which is the same as the global average. While that rate represents a decrease from the rate of the previous year (15.5 per cent), it remains higher than the pre-pandemic benchmark of 13.3 per cent in 2019. Beyond the regional aggregate, there are important divergences between sub-regions and countries in the evolution of unemployment rates and other labour market indicators. In both Southern and Eastern Asia, youth unemployment rates in 2022 are projected to be higher than the pre-pandemic benchmark by less than 1 percentage point, whereas in Southeast Asia and the Pacific, the corresponding rate is projected to be higher by 2 percentage points. In Sri Lanka, which is currently experiencing balance of payments and sovereign debt crises, youth unemployment in the second quarter of 2021 was at 30.0 per cent, whereas in Vietnam, which is benefiting from diversification strategies of global value chains as COVID-19 lockdowns in China persist, the corresponding rate for the same quarter was 5.5. per cent. Young men in the region face substantially higher unemployment rates (16.0 per cent) than young women (12.7 per cent). However, when examining a more comprehensive measure of labour underutilization, that is, the combined rate of youth unemployment and potential labour force (termed the LU3 rate), the gap between men and women diminishes, pointing to young women having higher potential labour force rates than young men.",Lifestyle and Features,2023-09-30 00:00:00
"Evergreen Nadal to the fore again, Spain in final","Madrid, November 24 Rafael Nadal inspired Spain into their first Davis Cup final since 2012 as he teamed up with Feliciano Lopez to secure a dramatic last-4 victory over Britain in Madrid. The hosts trailed 1-0 after Lopez's singles defeat to Kyle Edmund on Saturday, but Nadal thrashed Dan Evans before partnering Lopez in a 7-6(7) 7-6(10) win in the deciding doubles over Jamie Murray and Neal Skupski. Spain will face Canada in Sunday's final after the North Americans won their semifinal against Russia, which was also decided in the doubles rubber. ""It was a very special moment for us, a very unique opportunity,"" said the 38-year-old Lopez. ""We have a great opportunity to win this tournament here at home."" Denis Shapovalov and Vasek Pospisil sent Canada into their maiden Davis Cup showpiece by edging out Karen Khachanov and Andrey Rublev. Five-time champions Spain were indebted to world No. 1 Nadal for a virtuoso display as the 33-year-old continues his hunt for a fifth Davis Cup crown, having first lifted the title himself in 2004. ""This competition is always dramatic, especially with the new format,"" said Nadal. ""It's really, really special. Thank you to Feli (Lopez) and to the crowd who were amazing as well."" Spain lost their last Davis Cup sfinal to the Czech Republic six years ago. Edmund had earlier justified the decision of British captain Leon Smith to select him ahead of three-time Grand Slam champion Andy Murray by seeing off Lopez 6-3 7-6(7). But Nadal swatted aside Evans 6-4 6-0 to set up the doubles showdown. — AFP","Rafael Nadal propelled Spain to the Davis Cup final, overcoming a 1-0 deficit against Britain. Nadal defeated Dan Evans and then partnered with Feliciano Lopez for a 7-6(7) 7-6(10) win in the decisive doubles match. Spain will face Canada in the final. Nadal's outstanding performance marked Spain's return to the Davis Cup final since 2012",Sports,2019-11-25 00:00:00
"Meta unveils AI tool that can generate, edit videos based on text prompts","By Kurt Wagner Facebook parent Meta Platforms Inc. debuted a new artificial intelligence tool that can generate or edit videos based on a simple text prompt, elevating competition with rivals like OpenAI and Google in the race to develop the world’s most advanced AI technology. Meta’s product, Movie Gen, can create a new video up to 16 seconds long based on a text prompt. It can also use such prompts to generate audio for or edit an existing video, or even use a photo to create a customized video featuring a real person. Movie Gen is only available for some internal employees and a handful of outside partners, including some filmmakers, though the social media company — which also owns Instagram, WhatsApp and Messenger — plans to build the product into its existing apps sometime next year. Executives are still discussing how best to implement this integration, but the aim is for Movie Gen to encourage more people to create or edit video posts, said Connor Hayes, a Meta vice president focused on generative AI products. It will be “fun to use, helpful for creators, good for overall engagement in the apps, but we don’t have a concrete product plan of what it will look like at this point,” he said. The social networking leader is one of many major tech companies pushing into AI models focused on generating videos, which are more complicated and expensive to build than those that return AI-generated text. Microsoft Corp.-backed OpenAI has its own video generation tool, called Sora, that debuted earlier this year and can create videos up to a minute in length, though that technology isn’t available to the public yet. DeepMind, a subsidiary of Alphabet Inc.’s Google, also has a video generation tool, called Veo, which was unveiled earlier this year Meta is waiting to roll out Movie Gen for several reasons, including the technology’s efficiency. It currently takes “tens of minutes” to generate a video based on a text prompt — too long for general consumers, who are likely to use this on their phone, Hayes said. But Meta is also “sorting out a bunch of really important problems around safety and responsibility,” Hayes said, including how to handle personalized videos so that a user can’t create an inappropriate or unflattering video featuring another person without their consent. “That’s going to be probably the most important problem to solve before we would make the personalization capability available to folks broadly.”This type of technology has been used in the past to create misleading so-called deepfakes of famous people, including US President Joe Biden and pop star Taylor Swift, though Meta executives have said they’re working on ways to “watermark” these creations so that people can tell they’re AI-generated. Meta has made AI advancements a key priority for the entire company, and Chief Executive Officer Mark Zuckerberg has repeatedly talked about AI as a driver of user and revenue growth. In the short term, Zuckerberg has credited AI for helping improve the company’s content algorithms by showing people more relevant posts and advertisements. Eventually, Zuckerberg has said he believes AI will play an even larger role in powering its apps and other futuristic wearables Meta is producing, like smart glasses.","Meta Platforms Inc. has introduced Movie Gen, an AI tool capable of generating or editing videos based on text prompts, enhancing competition with companies like OpenAI and Google. Currently available to select employees and partners, Movie Gen can create videos up to 16 seconds long, generate audio, or customize existing videos using photos. Meta aims to integrate this tool into its apps next year, focusing on safety and ethical concerns, particularly regarding user consent in personalized videos. CEO Mark Zuckerberg sees AI as crucial for user engagement and revenue growth within the company.",Technology and Gadgets,2024-10-04 00:00:00
