"Need strategic planting of saplings, not just seed bombing for greener results: Experts","Panaji: The state has seen a plantation spree with students, teachers, and others planting seedlings and saplings. Tree lovers are drawing inspiration either from the monsoon greenery or the series of uprootings to plant more. Social media is abuzz with planting and seed bombing. But botanists and horticulturists have a few words of advice regarding the same. “The pits should be of sufficient size, according to the types of trees. A small pit would be okay for a small bag (seedling). It also depends on the soil; the softer the soil, the better the chances of survival,” said Sandeep Azrencar, an environmentalist. Thousands of saplings are planted, but the question remains—how many saplings will survive? Experts say several things must be kept in mind. Starting with the planting spot in terms of the right soil and the location. Another factor is the initial care and protection of the plant. The forest department that supplies lakhs of saplings for planting has two options of providing saplings—in big or small bags. “For them, it is uneconomical to use seedlings in big bags,” Azrencar said. The planting depends on the types of trees. “There are hardy varieties like gotting, tamarind, or satonn, which grow in open space. But zambul needs shade and watering initially,” he further said. Seed bombing is becoming popular, but some are wary about it. “It is a total no-no for city areas as the seeds will not take root,” says Daniel D’Souza, a landscape designer. The option is suitable for barren land and forest areas, Azrencar said. The quality of planting material and soil conditions are key factors for the survival of planted material. “Hence, if more saplings are planted, many may survive,” a forest department official said.","In Panaji, there's a growing trend of tree planting driven by monsoon greenery and recent deforestation. Social media is abuzz with planting and seed bombing, but experts stress proper techniques for success. Key factors include using appropriately sized planting pits, ensuring soil quality, and providing initial care. The forest department offers saplings in various bag sizes, with larger bags being more economical. Hardy tree species can grow in open areas, while others need shade and watering. Seed bombing is best suited for barren or forested areas, not urban environments. Proper planting practices increase the likelihood of sapling survival.",Environment,2024-07-30 00:00:00
Tata plant will spur growth in Bengal',"NEW DELHI: Undaunted by the opposition to acquisition of agricultural land at Singur for Tata's automobile plant that would produce the Nano, the West Bengal government has told the Supreme Court that the Singur venture would lead to rapid industrialisation of the state. ""The state government thinks that the implementation of the project at Singur will play a pivotal role with regard to developments in the field of modern industry in all respects not only in Singur, but also throughout the state of West Bengal,"" the Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee government said.The state was responding to the SC's notice to it on a petition filed by the Karnataka Landless Farmers Association, which was complaining against the states' recent policy to increasingly target agricultural land for setting up industries and SEZs. The West Bengal government refuted allegations that 645.67 acres of land had been leased out to Tatas at throwaway prices and said: ""The government has the power to form any policy and/or to exempt from paying various claims for the sake of greater interest of the state."" The association had alleged that soon 43,000 more acres of land would be acquired for two dozen companies of an available 2.25 lakh arable and arid land. Rejecting this, the state said: ""Though a few thousand acres of lands are under examination for setting up industrial units in different districts, out of which a major portion of land is not fit for cultivation or not at all fertile.""","Summary: West Bengal government defends the acquisition of agricultural land at Singur for Tata's automobile plant, arguing it will lead to rapid industrialization. Responding to a Supreme Court notice, it refutes allegations of leasing land at throwaway prices, citing greater state interests. Karnataka Landless Farmers Association had filed a petition.",Politics,2008-02-29 00:00:00
