TSNAB gets more teeth to curb drug menace,"Others Home » Nation » In Other News » January 3, 2024 NATION TSNAB gets more teeth to curb drug menace Deccan Chronicle.| DC Correspondent Published on: January 3, 2024 | Updated on: January 3, 2024 TSNAB TSNAB Hyderabad: To curb drug menace with an iron fist and break the spine of illicit drug supply chains, the state narcotics bureau has come up with a unique strategy to get to the main suppliers. The Telangana State Anti Narcotic Bureau (TSNAB), after conducting research on previous cases of drug peddling/supplying that were detected, have decided to target the consumers and suppliers with their latest intelligence and advanced equipment sanctioned by the state government recently. Earlier the narcotic bureau used to focus on the peddlers more but as the demand for drugs has multiplied the rate of consumers and suppliers have drastically increased. ""We have identified drug peddlers but we need to dig into it to break the main supplier chain,"" a TSNAB officer said. ""We are sharing intelligence on drugs with agencies across borders to identify the main foreign suppliers involved in smuggling drugs into the country and will act accordingly,"" TSNAB director Sandeep Shandilya told Deccan Chronicle.","The Telangana State Anti Narcotic Bureau (TSNAB) adopts a strategy targeting consumers and suppliers, backed by advanced equipment, to intensify efforts against the drug menace and dismantle illicit supply chains, focusing on intelligence sharing with international agencies to identify foreign suppliers.",National News,2024-01-03 00:00:00
"""Rajan roasts RBI for corporate bank idea""","The headline ""Rajan roasts RBI for corporate bank idea"" - Nov 24, 2020 from The New Indian Express refers to the criticism of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI)'s proposal to allow large non-financial companies to own banks in India by former RBI Governor Raghuram Rajan. Rajan argued that allowing large non-financial companies to own banks would lead to increased concentration of ownership in the banking sector and make the sector more vulnerable to shocks. He also argued that it would lead to conflicts of interest, as the non-financial companies would be able to use the banks to finance their own businesses. The RBI's proposal to allow large non-financial companies to own banks is a controversial one. There are both potential benefits and risks associated with the proposal. It is important to carefully consider all of the factors involved before making a decision about whether or not to allow large non-financial companies to own banks.","Former RBI Governor Raghuram Rajan criticized the Reserve Bank of India's (RBI) proposal to allow large non-financial companies to own banks in India. Rajan argued that the proposal would lead to increased concentration of ownership in the banking sector, making it more vulnerable to shocks. He also argued that it would lead to conflicts of interest, as the non-financial companies would be able to use the banks to finance their own businesses.","India news, business news, banking news",2020-11-24 00:00:00
Chandrayaan-1: The first time India ‘touched’ the Moon,"Chandrayaan-1 carried a module called the Moon Impact Probe, which was dropped to the lunar surface as proof of India’s arrival. Madhavan, what evidence are you going to show before the world that we reached the Moon?” APJ Abdul Kalam asked G Madhavan Nair, the chairman of Isro (2003-2009), prior to the launch of Chandrayaan-1 in 2008. “When we carried out missions to Everest and Antarctica, we placed our flag there. In the case of the Moon mission, we are relying to convince the world with a lot of digital data. Don’t you think we should do something more?” Dr Kalam asked. At the time he raised this question, Dr Kalam was the President of India and the country’s most respected scientific mind. Nair writes in his autobiographical work Rocketing Through the Skies: An Eventful Life at ISRO (2023), that this one simple question modified his entire perspective – giving birth to the concept of the Moon Impact Probe (MIP), carried aboard Chandrayaan-1. As Chandrayaan-3 lands on the Moon today, we recall when India first “planted a flag” on the Moon. India’s first foray to the Moon Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee (1924-2018) announced India’s moon mission in his Independence Day speech in 2003. This would be India’s first foray outside Earth’s gravitational pull and the most challenging task undertaken by the Indian Space Research Organisation (Isro) until then.","Yamunotri Temple is a sacred Hindu shrine nestled in the serene Himalayan mountains of Uttarakhand, India. Dedicated to Goddess Yamuna, the temple holds great religious significance for devotees who believe that a pilgrimage to this sacred site cleanses them of sins and ensures divine blessings. Situated at an elevation of about 3,293 meters (10,804 feet) above sea level, reaching Yamunotri involves a trek through picturesque landscapes and challenging terrains. The temple is surrounded by snow-capped peaks and lush greenery, creating a breathtaking atmosphere for spiritual seekers. The main deity, Goddess Yamuna, is worshipped in the form of a black marble idol adorned with flowers and garments. The temple's hot water spring, called Surya Kund, is an integral part of the pilgrimage, as devotees cook rice and potatoes in the naturally heated water to offer as Prasad (sacred food). Yamunotri Temple is not just a religious site; it is also a cultural and natural treasure. Pilgrims and tourists alike visit to experience the divine aura and marvel at the beauty of the Himalayan surroundings. The journey to Yamunotri is not merely a physical trek but a spiritual odyssey, fostering a connection between the devotee and the divine in the lap of nature's grandeu",Technology and Gadgets,2023-08-24 00:00:00
Trains’ suspension extended till Aug 12,"New Delhi : Passenger trains, including express and suburban services that were earlier suspended till June 30, will not operate till August 12, according to an internal circular of the railway board on Thursday. The 15 pairs of premium Rajdhani trains connecting Delhi with different parts of the country, which began on May 12, and 100 pairs of long-distance trains, which began on June 1, will continue to function. “It has been decided that regular time-tabled passenger services including Mail/Express, passenger and suburban services stand cancelled up to 12.08.2020,” the railway board said in a notification. All tickets booked for the regular time-tabled trains from July 1 to August 12, too, stood cancelled and full fares will be refunded to passengers. “It has also been decided that all the ticket booked for the regular time-tabled trains for the journey date from 01.07.20 to 12.08.20 also stand cancelled,” the circular said. A spokesperson for the railway ministry said no trains that are presently operational have been withdrawn. Shramik Special trains, which are ferrying migrants to their hometown, too, will operate as per requirements. “As far as running of more trains are concerned, all will be informed and bookings will be done as and when a decision is taken about them,” he added. The railway ministry, in a notification on May 15, cancelled all trains scheduled for travel till June 30, and decided to refund the ticket fares. Passenger train services were halted on March 22, three days before the imposition of a national lockdown on March 25 that was aimed at containing the coronavirus disease. Freight and parcel trains have operated in the lockdown period.","Indian Railways has decided to extend the suspension of regular passenger train services until August 12, 2020, in response to the ongoing Covid-19 crisis. While routine services remain halted, select Rajdhani and long-distance trains will continue operating, along with the Shramik Special trains for migrants. Passengers with bookings from July 1 to August 12 will receive full refunds as these services stand canceled. The suspension, which began in March before the nationwide lockdown, remains in place to curb the virus spread. Authorities have assured that any updates on restarting additional services will be communicated in due time.",Health and Wellness,2020-06-26 00:00:00
"Both State, Central Govts are anti-farmer'","Hundreds of farmers under the banner of the Akhila Bharat Krushak Sangathan Samannwaya Samiti and the All India Kishan Sangharsh Coordination Committee (AIKSCC), Odisha chapter, took to the streets here on Monday raising various issues concerning farmers’ community in the State and the country. Farmers from various districts across the State staged a ‘Krushak Adhikar Chetabani Samavesh’ holding banners and shouting slogans against Government’s apathy towards the community. A team of representatives from the neighbouring State of West Bengal and the Sarba Bharatiya Kishan Sangharsh Jatha (Jatra) also joined the stir. Environmentalist and farmer leader Prafulla Samantray joined the protest and termed both the State Government and the Centre as anti-farmer. He alleged that the State Government is yet to give bonus to the farmers and urged the Centre to increase the paddy MSP to Rs 2,930 per quintal. Similarly, the Centre hiked the paddy MSP by a mere Rs 80 when the Prime Minister had earlier promised to double the price. Besides, no steps have been taken to waive farm loans, he added. Jai Kisan Andolan founder Yogendra Yadav said if Chief Minister Naveen Patnaik is not able to solve the problems of farmers at least he should accept the farmer’s suicide in the State. Till date the country had a number of Prime Ministers but none of them is anti-farmer like Prime Minister Narendra Modi, he added. Members of the various national organisatons alleged that farmers are not the getting remunerative prices of their produces. They mentioned that due to the burden of agricultural loan, as many as 36,000 farmers have committed suicide during the three-year tenure of the Modi Government. They said many companies have looted about Rs 21,500 crore as premium from the State and Central Governments under the Pradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana. They said that the country’s 121 crore people are dependent upon the farmers, but the farmers are most neglected. They demanded that the State and Central Government free farmers from the dept trap, to provide profitable MSP for all agricultural produces as per the Swaminathan Commission recommendation, provide land to landless, concede forest rights to the tribals and forest dwellers and provide Rs 5,000 monthly pension to all farmers. AIKSCC convenor VM Singh, All India Kisan Sabha general secretary Hannan Mollah, Kisan Sangharsh Samiti, Madhya Pradesh president Dr Sunilam, Odisha Krushak Sabha’s (OKS) Suresh Panigrahi, All India Kishan Mahasabha’s (AIKM) Ashok Pradhan, All India Kishan Majdoor Sabha’s (AIKMS) Bhalachandra Sarangi and others spoke on the anti-farmer policies of the State and Central Governments.","Farmers from various districts in Odisha, organized by Akhila Bharat Krushak Sangathan Samannwaya Samiti and All India Kishan Sangharsh Coordination Committee (AIKSCC), protested against the government's neglect of farmers' issues. They demanded higher MSP for paddy, farm loan waivers, and criticized the Pradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana for benefiting companies more than farmers. The protest also highlighted concerns over farmer suicides and called for comprehensive support including land for landless farmers, forest rights for tribals, and a monthly pension of Rs 5,000 for all farmers. Leaders like Yogendra Yadav and VM Singh criticized both the state and central governments for their alleged anti-farmer policies.",Politics,2017-10-31 00:00:00
