"Oscars 2022 moves to late March, keeps 2021 pandemic eligibility rules","Planning is already underway for the 94th Oscars, which will be held on March 27, 2022, the film academy and ABC said on Thursday. After a year of disruption, innovation and catastrophically low ratings, the Academy Awards are getting back to business as usual. The show will return to the Dolby Theatre for its ABC broadcast and the eligibility window will once again close at the end of the calendar year. This past year, the academy extended the eligibility window into February and cancelled non-televised events like the Governors Awards and the Nominees Luncheon because of the pandemic. All those trimmings are now back on the schedule, with the Governors Awards set for January 15 and the luncheon to be held on March 7. Nominations will be announced on February 8. The academy said, however, that dates remain subject to change. The organisation is also acknowledging that the movie business is still being impacted by the pandemic and are extending the streaming eligibility caveat they adopted last year into the 2021 awards season. That means that films don’t necessarily have to have a theatrical run to qualify and can debut on streaming or video on demand services. The end of March broadcast date is much later than usual for Hollywood’s biggest awards show. Originally the 94th edition was set to air on February 27, but that month is also crowded with major live events, including the 2022 Olympics and the Super Bowl.","Planning for the 94th Oscars is underway, with the ceremony scheduled for March 27, 2022, the Academy and ABC announced. After a disrupted year marked by low ratings and pandemic-related changes, the Oscars will return to the Dolby Theatre with the eligibility period reverting to the calendar year’s end. Traditional events like the Governors Awards (January 15) and the Nominees Luncheon (March 7) are back on the calendar, with nominations announced on February 8. The Academy will continue allowing films that premiere on streaming or video-on-demand platforms to qualify without a theatrical run, reflecting ongoing pandemic impacts. The March date, later than usual, avoids clashes with major events like the Winter Olympics and the Super Bowl.",Entertainment,2021-05-27 00:00:00
