"LS election: Overseas voter turnout drops to 2.5% from 25.6% in 2019; nil in TN, Karnataka","Compared to the 2019 Lok Sabha elections, overseas voters turnout in the 2024 general elections plunged to 2.47 per cent from 25.64 per cent, showed an analysis of a recent statistical report shared by the Election Commission. The elections saw the BJP-led NDA government returning to power and the INDIA bloc gaining numerical strength in the Lok Sabha. There were 1,19,374 registered overseas electors in 2024, however, only 2,958 of them exercised their franchise at the respective polling booths in India, the report’s analysis showed. In 2019, there were a total of 99,844 overseas voters and of them, 25,606 cast their votes. Of the 17 states and UTs where overseas electors are registered, those in seven states and two UTs exercised their franchise. Five states — Kerala, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Tamil Nadu and Karnataka — comprise 90 per cent of the country’s total overseas electors. Of them, turnout was nil in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka in the 2024 Lok Sabha elections. Highest enrolment of overseas electors in 2024 was recorded in five southern states – Kerala (89,839), Andhra Pradesh (7,927), Telangana (3,470), Tamil Nadu (3,432) and Karnataka (3,148). Kerala’s turnout dropped from 29.13 per cent in 2019 to 2.97 per cent in 2024, diminishing the overall turnout of overseas voters this year. Andhra Pradesh’s turnout, on the other hand, improved from five of 5,090 registered voters casting their votes to 195 of 7,927 voting this time. Telangana’s turnout also rose marginally from nil in 2019 to three out of 3,470 electors casting their votes. In seven states — Arunachal Pradesh, Manipur, Mizoram, Nagaland, Sikkim, Tripura, J&K — no new overseas voter registered for the 2024 polls. Same was the case for three UTs — Andaman and Nicobar, Lakshadweep, and Ladakh. In the northeast, Meghalaya was an exception with five registered voters, but no one turned up on the day of voting. In Maharashtra, which has the third-largest number of overseas electors of 5,097, only 17 of them cast their votes. In Uttar Pradesh, where INDIA bloc secured more seats than NDA, none of 859 overseas electors turned up to vote, while six of 244 registered electors voted in 2019. In Punjab, 13 out of 1,613 registered voters cast their votes, while 33 of 1,523 overseas electors voted in 2019. Haryana’s turnout went up from nil in 2019 to 37 voters casting their votes. Though the number of registered voters went up in Rajasthan from 194 in 2019 to 289 this year, turnout was nil. As per the Election Commission, an overseas voter must be a citizen of India and has not acquired citizenship of any other country and is otherwise eligible to be registered as a voter, who is absenting from his place of ordinary residence in India owing to his employment","Overseas voter turnout in the 2024 Lok Sabha elections dropped drastically to 2.47%, compared to 25.64% in 2019, as per Election Commission data. Out of 1,19,374 registered overseas electors, only 2,958 voted at polling booths in India. In contrast, 25,606 of 99,844 overseas voters had cast their votes in 2019. The majority of overseas voters are from five southern states — Kerala, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Tamil Nadu, and Karnataka — accounting for 90% of the total. Kerala, which has the highest number of overseas voters, saw a steep decline in turnout from 29.13% in 2019 to 2.97% in 2024. Tamil Nadu and Karnataka recorded zero turnout. Some states like Andhra Pradesh and Telangana witnessed a slight improvement. Several northeastern states and union territories had no registered overseas voters. Despite rising registration in some areas, actual voter participation sharply declined, raising concerns about accessibility and engagement of overseas citizens in India’s electoral process.",Politics,2024-12-29 00:00:00
