Bmc To Send Pending Tax Bills Soon | Kolkata News,"Bidhannagar Municipal Corporation (BMC ) will start sending property tax bills to assessees for the first and second quarters along with all outstanding dues from April 26 onwards. Taxpayers will have the opportunity to pay their dues till September 30. The civic body aims to collect Rs 40 crore from property tax this financial year. As per records available with the civic body, the total tax dues now stand at Rs 65 crore, out of which Rs 33 crore is left from the Salt Lake areas and the rest from the Rajarhat-Gopalpur areas.BMC have been holding regular camps across wards to raise awareness.","The Bidhannagar Municipal Corporation (BMC) is set to dispatch property tax bills to assesses for the first and second quarters, including all outstanding dues, starting from April 26. Taxpayers will have until September 30 to make payments. The BMC aims to collect Rs 40 crore in property tax for the current financial year. The total outstanding tax dues currently amount to Rs 65 crore, with Rs 33 crore from Salt Lake areas and the remaining from Rajarhat-Gopalpur areas. The BMC has conducted awareness camps across wards to inform and educate taxpayers about the process.",Business and Finance,2023-04-02 00:00:00
GST launched: India gets unified tax regime,"India launched the Goods and Services Tax (GST) on Saturday, July 1, 2017, marking a major milestone in the country's economic history. GST is a unified tax regime that has replaced a complex web of central and state taxes. The launch of GST was a major achievement for the Indian government. It was the culmination of years of planning and negotiation. GST is expected to simplify the tax system, reduce tax burden on businesses, and boost economic growth. The launch of GST was also a major challenge. Businesses had to scramble to comply with the new tax regime. There were also some initial glitches in the GST system. Despite the challenges, the launch of GST was a major success. It was a historic moment for India. GST is expected to have a significant impact on the Indian economy and society.","The Goods and Services Tax (GST) is a unified tax regime that has replaced a complex web of central and state taxes in India. GST is levied on the supply of goods and services. It is a destination-based tax, i.e., the tax is collected at the state where the goods or services are consumed. The GST was launched on July 1, 2017. It is a major achievement for the Indian government and a historic moment for India. GST is expected to simplify the tax system, reduce tax burden on businesses, and boost economic growth.",Miscellaneous,2017-07-01 00:00:00
2024 Hyundai Creta to launch in India tomorrow: Here are price expectations,"Hyundai is gearing up for the highly anticipated release of the 2024 Creta in the Indian market, scheduled for Tuesday. Since its initial introduction in 2015, the Creta has amassed a customer base exceeding 9.80 lakh in nearly nine years. Despite facing strong competition in the mid-size SUV segment, the Creta has consistently maintained its leadership position. The upcoming Hyundai Creta showcases notable alterations to its exterior design, improvements to the interior layout, an expanded array of features, and the introduction of Level 2 Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS). As per a report by HT Auto, it is highly likely that the pricing for the 2024 Hyundai Creta will surpass the current cost structure of the second-generation model. Currently, the Creta is priced between Rs10.90 lakh and Rs19.20 lakh (ex-showroom). While the base variant of the 2024 Creta may retain its current pricing at Rs10.90 lakh (ex-showroom), similar to its main rival, the Kia Seltos, which was updated last year, as one progresses through the variant range, there could be an increase ranging from Rs20,000 to Rs50,000. The highest-tier diesel model of the Creta is anticipated to be priced in the range of Rs12 lakh to Rs22 lakh (ex-showroom). The addition of the 1.5-liter turbo petrol engine adds an intriguing element, available exclusively in the top-tier variant and expected to be priced at approximately Rs21 lakh (ex-showroom). Speaking of powertrain, the new Creta from Hyundai will feature the inclusion of the 1.5-liter Turbo GDi Petrol engine. Additionally, the Creta lineup will encompass options like the 1.5-liter MPi petrol and 1.5-liter U2 CRDi diesel engines. Regarding transmission alternatives, the revamped Creta will provide a choice of six-speed manual, Intelligent Variable Transmission (IVT), seven-speed Dual Clutch Transmission (DCT), and six-speed automatic transmission. It's important to highlight that the turbo petrol engine will exclusively be paired with the seven-speed DCT. The 2024 Hyundai Creta will be available in a comprehensive range of seven main variants, namely E, EX, S, S(O), SX, SX Tech, and SX (O). Milestone Alert! Livemint tops charts as the fastest growing news website in the world Click here to know more. Unlock a world of Benefits! From insightful newsletters to real-time stock tracking, breaking news and a personalized newsfeed - it's all here, just a click away! Login Now!","The addition of the 1.5-liter turbo petrol engine adds an intriguing element, available exclusively in the top-tier variant and expected to be priced at approximately Rs21 lakh (ex-showroom). The highest-tier diesel model of the Creta is anticipated to be priced in the range of Rs12 lakh to Rs22 lakh (ex-showroom). Currently, the Creta is priced between Rs10.90 lakh and Rs19.20 lakh (ex-showroom). Additionally, the Creta lineup will encompass options like the 1.5-liter MPi petrol and 1.5-liter U2 CRDi diesel engines. Regarding transmission alternatives, the revamped Creta will provide a choice of six-speed manual, Intelligent Variable Transmission (IVT), seven-speed Dual Clutch Transmission (DCT), and six-speed automatic transmission. The 2024 Hyundai Creta will be available in a comprehensive range of seven main variants, namely E, EX, S, S(O), SX, SX Tech, and SX (O). It's important to highlight that the turbo petrol engine will exclusively be paired with the seven-speed DCT. Speaking of powertrain, the new Creta from Hyundai will feature the inclusion of the 1.5-liter Turbo GDi Petrol engine. Since its initial introduction in 2015, the Creta has amassed a customer base exceeding 9.80 lakh in nearly nine years. Click here to know more. Unlock a world of Benefits!",National News,2024-01-15 00:00:00
Few M&As in 2001; but many big-ticket deals,"The year 2001 witnessed a slowdown in the mergers and acquisitions (M&A) activity, with fewer deals being announced and completed, compared to the previous year. However, the year also saw several big-ticket deals, involving large corporations and strategic investors, which had a significant impact on the market and the industry. The slowdown in the M&A activity can be attributed to various factors, such as the economic downturn, the uncertainty and volatility in the financial markets, and the regulatory and legal challenges. However, the big-ticket deals, which were driven by strategic considerations, such as market consolidation, synergy, and diversification, demonstrated the resilience and dynamism of the corporate sector, and the potential for growth and innovation.","The year 2001 witnessed a slowdown in the mergers and acquisitions (M&A) activity, with fewer deals being announced and completed, compared to the previous year. However, the year also saw several big-ticket deals, involving large corporations and strategic investors, which had a significant impact on the market and the industry. The slowdown in the M&A activity can be attributed to various factors, such as the economic downturn, the uncertainty and volatility in the financial markets, and the regulatory and legal challenges.",Business and Finance,2001-12-25 00:00:00
"Work stress could be reason for suicides in BSF, says study","A study conducted byBorder Security Force(BSF) suggests that the sentinels of the country’s borders are not living in very good conditions and are unhappy with certain facilities which could have helped reduce their occupational stress. This in turn could be leading to suicides/fratricides and personnel leaving the job without thinking about their future.Conducted byGyaneshwar Singh, second-in-command of 166th battalion at BSF’s North Bengal Frontier, the study looks at the level of occupational stress in the force due to non-operational factors (non-work stressors).“Occupational stress is impelling the personnel either to take the extreme step of suicide/fratricide to overcome the stress, or to leave the job without having any certainty about their future,” says the study, which has been approved by the top brass of BSF, the two lakh strong force which guards India’s borders with Pakistan andBangladesh.Talking about the trust deficit among senior command and lower ranks in the force, the BSF study says that there is a need to develop a culture of open expression and regular dialogue between the commanders and those under their command (jawans), “which is (presently) missing in the organisation”. It goes on to say that the present relationship in BSF between commanders and lower ranks is of “authoritarian” nature, which is a one way system.The research has looked at living conditions of jawans at the borders and other places of posting, their families, finances, and relationship with seniors to establish how these things lead to occupational stress.About the living barracks of jawans, the study says that around 43.7% of personnel have termed the conditions of living barracks (at places of posting) as ‘satisfactory,’ while 20.4% have said it is ‘bad’ and 4.8% claim it is ‘very bad’. Only 7.6 % BSF personnel have rated the living barracks as “very good” while 22.6 % have rated them as “good”.About 94.5% BSF personnel have stated that they need cleanliness in toilets, numbers of cots and fans increased at the barracks. The living conditions of jawans and the fact that they get less time to sleep adds to their woes and hence their motivational level is really affected, which further causes “stress”, it says. The command level officers interviewed by researchers agreed even though they make efforts to provide the basic amenities to the troops deployed on border but “there are always one or the other limitation”. “It is true that we haven’t been able to provide comfortable and healthy living conditions on border,” the senior officers admit.On whether the jawans are appreciated for their work or not, it says that 51% personnel feel that their work is not appreciated whle about 42% feel it is appreciated. “It is an important factor which has direct bearing on the motivation and morale. Some troops opine that the task assigned to them are fulfilled with great zeal and enthusiasm but no recognition is shown towards them,” the study says.Asserting that ‘family’ is the main non-operational factor which is the strongest ‘stressor’ for occupational stress in the force, the study says, “There are various issues related to family. It is not only the separation from the family but their well-being and settlement also raises a worry for the person who is deployed at border.” “…..the occupational stress has direct bearing on the productivity and motivation of the organisation.Moreover the lesser the motivation, the lesser is the commitment or the involvement which can also be termed as employee engagement,” study says, adding that “occupational stress which has now become a common phenomenon and a subject in discussion.”","A study conducted by the Border Security Force (BSF) indicates that BSF personnel are facing occupational stress due to various non-operational factors, which could be contributing to incidents of suicide, fratricide, and personnel leaving the job. The study highlights issues related to living conditions, a lack of appreciation for their work, and concerns about their families' well-being and settlement as significant stressors for BSF personnel. It also emphasizes the need for better living conditions, improved communication between commanders and lower ranks, and recognition for their efforts to address occupational stress in the force. The study's findings have been approved by the top brass of the BSF, which guards India's borders with Pakistan and Bangladesh.",Lifestyle and Features,2017-12-24 00:00:00
Vaishali Rameshbabu earns final Grandmaster Norm at Qatar Masters,"Qatar Masters 2023 witnessed a momentous occasion as Vaishali Rameshbabu, the talented 22-year-old and sister of R Praggnanandhaa. She secured her third and final Grandmaster (GM) norm. Despite losing her final round game against the renowned GM Gregory Kaidanov, Vaishali’s remarkable performance throughout the tournament ensured her place as the best women’s player at the prestigious event. As the game concluded, a wave of congratulations poured in for Vaishali. GM Kaidanov himself extended his heartfelt praise for the young talent, recognising her achievement in acquiring the final GM norm. Vaishali’s mother, Nagalakshmi, stood by her side, radiating with pride as her daughter signed autographs, relishing the memorable moment, just like she does when Praggnanandhaa is playing.","Chess player Vaishali Rameshbabu has achieved her final Grandmaster Norm at the prestigious Qatar Masters tournament. This accomplishment is a remarkable milestone in the world of chess and signifies that Vaishali has met the stringent performance requirements needed to attain the coveted title of Grandmaster. Earning a Grandmaster Norm necessitates an exceptional display of skill and strategic prowess in chess, as well as reaching specific rating benchmarks. The Grandmaster title is the highest accolade in the chess world, signifying a player's profound understanding of the game and their exceptional abilities. Vaishali Rameshbabu's achievement highlights her dedication, talent, and relentless efforts in the realm of chess. It marks a significant step in her career and a testament to her excellence in the game. Her accomplishment at the Qatar Masters is a momentous recognition of her skills and places her among the elite echelons of the chess world.",Sports,2023-10-21 00:00:00
