SC dismisses pleas to review Article 370 judgment,"A Bench of five judges headed by Chief Justice of India D.Y. Chandrachud has dismissed multiple petitions seeking a review of a Supreme Court judgment upholding the abrogation of Article 370 in August 2019. “Having perused the review petitions, there is no error apparent on the face of the record. No case for review under Order XLVII Rule 1 of the Supreme Court Rules 2013. The review petitions are, therefore, dismissed,” the Review Bench passed a short order recently. The Review Bench, besides the CJI, comprised Justices Sanjiv Khanna, B.R. Gavai, Surya Kant and A.S. Bopanna. A Constitution Bench had upheld the abrogation of Article 370, an event which had led to the reorganisation of the full-fledged State of Jammu and Kashmir to two union territories and denuding it of its special privileges. The judgment, in November 2023, had confirmed that the President could “unilaterally issue a notification that Article 370 ceases to exist”. The court had held that the President has power to abrogate Article 370 if “special circumstances warranted a special solution”. The court had said the abrogation of Article 370 was the culmination of a “gradual and collaborative exercise” spread over the past 70 years between the Centre and the State to integrate Jammu and Kashmir with the Union.","A five-judge Bench, led by Chief Justice of India D.Y. Chandrachud, recently dismissed multiple petitions seeking a review of the Supreme Court's judgment that upheld the abrogation of Article 370 in August 2019. The court found no error apparent on the record and dismissed the petitions. The earlier judgment, delivered in November 2023, affirmed that the President had the power to unilaterally issue a notification to revoke Article 370, which had granted special privileges to Jammu and Kashmir. The court justified the decision, stating that it was a culmination of a long process of integration between Jammu and Kashmir and the Union over several decades.",National News,2024-05-21 00:00:00
Killer virus waiting to hit,"LUCKNOW: After SARS, Avian Influenza and deadly Aids virus scientists are now fearing the outbreak of another pandemic or killer influenza similar to the flu epidemic that killed millions of people worldwide in 1918. According to Prof David J Triggle from the University of Buffalo, the influenza virus keeps mutating and becoming more drug-resistant every year. Pharmacologists have to variate the composition of the Flu Shot or influenza vaccine each year in order to counter the new highly drug resilient strains of influenza. Another disturbing factor is that most of the antibiotics available in the market have already developed a drug resistance. Rampant misuse of antibiotics, self prescription and over-subscription in addition to pumping antibiotics in the food of poultry and animal livestock is responsible for non-responsiveness to antibiotics. He added that scientists today are battling against time in order to find new arenas and compounds for developing potent antibiotic targets as we are fast running out of effective antibiotic drugs. Faulty, unscientific farming practices have exacerbated the problem. ""China in fact is fast emerging as the ''factory for producing influenza''. This is primarily because China has a unique farming practice wherein pig and ducks are living in close proximity. The influenza virus ensures its existence by simply mutating each time it transfers itself from the pigs to the ducks to the chicken and so on,"" he said. He emphasised that it must be remembered that the deadly Aids virus was also first traced in the monkeys. It was only when it got transferred from the monkeys to human beings that it mutated into a much more virulent and killer form. ""We are constantly witnessing the spiking of certain ''mysterious diseases'' that wipe out a certain section of the susceptible populations and go largely uninvestigated and unreported. Earlier, since the disease was concentrated in a certain pocket it did not matter. In a global village with people constantly jet setting across the world the dangers are far more enhanced as the diseases are also easily crossing borders,"" he added.","Scientists, including Prof David J Triggle from the University of Buffalo, are expressing concerns about the potential outbreak of a new pandemic, similar to the deadly flu epidemic of 1918. The influenza virus constantly mutates, evolving into more drug-resistant strains each year. This necessitates the annual adjustment of the Flu Shot or influenza vaccine to counteract the evolving virus. Compounding the problem is the widespread development of drug resistance in most antibiotics available on the market. Misuse, self-prescription, over-subscription, and the use of antibiotics in poultry and livestock contribute to this non-responsiveness. Faulty and unscientific farming practices, particularly in China, are identified as a major concern. The close proximity of pigs, ducks, and chickens in Chinese farming facilitates the influenza virus's continuous mutation. Prof Triggle emphasizes the need to find new compounds for potent antibiotic targets as effective antibiotic drugs are running out. He draws parallels with the emergence of the deadly AIDS virus, originally traced in monkeys and later mutating into a more virulent form in humans. In the interconnected global village, where diseases easily cross borders, the potential for uninvestigated and unreported mysterious diseases poses a significant threat.",Health and Wellness,2004-02-25 00:00:00
