Sixth sense? Human beings can detect magnetic fields,"WASHINGTON: Humans may have a sixth sense after all, scientists have suggested, after finding that a protein in the human retina, when placed into fruit flies, has the ability to detect magnetic fields. The researchers from the University of Massachusetts Medical School, however, cautioned that whether or not humans use it in that way is not known. For the study, published in the journal Nature Communications , lead researcher Steven Reppert and his team carried out several experiments on wild fruit flies. The team replaced the cryptochromes of some fruit flies with the human version of the protein. They placed the flies into a T-shaped maze, with each arm equipped with a coil wrapped in such a way that when a current was sent through it, the coil became magnetized. The flies with the human cryptochromes showed sensitivity to the magnetic fields — either avoiding them as they might naturally do if, or showing a preference for the magnetised arm of the maze when trained with sugar rewards to go toward the magnetic field.","Researchers from the University of Massachusetts Medical School conducted experiments on wild fruit flies, replacing their cryptochromes with the human version of the protein. They found that the flies with human cryptochromes showed sensitivity to magnetic fields when placed in a T-shaped maze with magnetized coils. The flies either avoided the magnetic fields or showed a preference for the magnetized arm of the maze when trained with sugar rewards. This suggests that the protein in the human retina may have the ability to detect magnetic fields, hinting at the possibility of a sixth sense in humans. However, whether humans actually use this ability is yet to be determined.",Science and Technology,2011-06-23 00:00:00
