A ray of hope in eradicating diarrhoea from India,"Every year nearly 11 children die every year before the age of five, due to disease that are easily preventable. In India itself more children under the age of five die as compared to any part of the world. Out of which diarrhoea has been the major cause of deaths amongst kids. Sad fact but very true. To overcome or combat this problem, UNICEF launched a 5 million USD programme in India on 3rd of April, 2013. The programme consists of providing zinc supplementation and oral rehydration therapy to prevent diarrhoea n young children. This programme will help to save over 150,000 children’s lives in India. The main aim of the programme is to treat diarrhoea and strengthen Indian health care system by up scaling the use of zinc supplementation and oral rehydration salts. In India, only 2 percent of children are accessible to zinc and ORS-which is cost-effective and life-saving mode of diarrhoea treatment. This new programme will help to save 150,000 children's lives over the course of the five-year programme, and 50,000 lives annually going forward, in Uttar Pradesh, Odisha and Madhya Pradesh alone. These three states accounts for the highest problem of childhood diarrhoea. Mr. David Morley- UNICEF Canada's President says - ""This new initiative exemplifies the considerable contributions corporate partnerships can make towards improving the lives of the world's most vulnerable children. UNICEF's partnership with Teck in India will provide strategic investments in proven interventions.” Besides, improving the health condition of children this programme will also help to educate health workers and communities while strengthening the local supply chain to ensure zinc and ORS are accessible and that achievements made over the next five years are sustainable in the long term. Mr. Doug Horswill-Senior Vice President at Teck says, ""In India, the number of children dying from diarrhoea, an illness that can be treated with zinc and ORS is particularly dire. As one of the world's largest producers of zinc, we have the ability and knowledge to help address this critical children's health issue.""","UNICEF launched a $5 million programme in India on April 3, 2013, aimed at preventing childhood deaths from easily preventable diseases. Focusing on diarrhoea, which claims the lives of over 150,000 children annually in India, the initiative aims to provide zinc supplementation and oral rehydration therapy. Targeting Uttar Pradesh, Odisha, and Madhya Pradesh, where childhood diarrhoea is most prevalent, the programme seeks to save 150,000 children's lives over five years. Teck, a key partner, will contribute expertise in zinc production. The initiative also emphasizes community education and strengthening local healthcare systems to ensure sustainability beyond the programme's duration.",Lifestyle and Features,2013-04-11 00:00:00
