"City can tackle vehicle pollution, say experts","PUNE: The Dehradun-based Indian Institute of Petroleum (IIP), which conducted an extensive study on vehicular pollution in Pune city, has expressed confidence that the introduction of stricter emission norms would help substantially reduce emission levels by the year 2011.The institute has estimated that these reductions will occur in two phases: up to 2005 after the introduction of Bharat Stage II emission norms and between 2005-10, after the full implementat-ion of Bharat Stage II norms for two-wheelers, and Stage III norms for other vehicles till 2010.According to the institute, in the first phase, carbon monoxide (CO) emissions may be expected to drop by 591 tonnes, hydrocarbons (HC) and nitrogen oxides (NOx) by 176 tonnes and particulate matter (PM) by 33 tonnes.At the end of the second phase in 2010, introduction of stricter emission norms could help reduce CO emissions by 5,039 tonnes, HC and NOx by 873 tonnes and PM by 13 tonnes.The report was submitted to the national auto fuel policy committee headed by director-general of the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research R.A. Mashelkar in September, following which the committee recommended that the Bharat Stage II emission norms for new vehicles be implemented in Pune on a priority, along with some other cities.The study â€” An assessment of automotive emission scenario of Pune city â€” has assumed that vehicle population will grow by 8 per cent till 2010-11, resulting from the addition of 4.20 lakh two-wheelers, 42,000 three-wheelers, 7,000 petrol- and diesel-driven cars and taxis each, 500 buses and 3,000 trucks. Explore Your Financial Landscape with Personalized Credit Insights.","A study by the Indian Institute of Petroleum predicts significant reductions in vehicular pollution in Pune by 2011 due to stricter emission norms (Bharat Stage II and III). From 2005-2010, CO emissions are projected to drop by 591 tonnes, hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides by