"US Guv, Google boss arrive in N Korea","Former New Mexico Governor Bill Richardson and Google Executive Chairman Eric Schmidt began a controversial private mission to North Korea on Monday that may include an effort to secure the release of an imprisoned American, the media reported. The trip comes after North Korea carried out a long range rocket test last month and as the reclusive state continues work on its nuclear testing facilities according to satellite imagery, potentially paving the way for a third nuclear bomb test. South Korean broadcaster MBC said the delegation comprising Schmidt, his daughter, Richardson and Google executive Jared Cohen were due to travel to Pyongyang from Beijing on North Korean state carrier Air Koryo. North Korea's KCNA state news agency later said they had arrived. It gave no details. The mission has been criticised by the White House due to the sensitivity of the timing. The United States does not have diplomatic relations with North Korea and the isolated and impoverished state remains technically at war with South Korea. South Korea is in the midst of a transition to a new President who will take office in February. — Reuters","Former New Mexico Governor Bill Richardson and Google Executive Chairman Eric Schmidt embarked on a private mission to North Korea on Monday, with the aim of possibly securing the release of an imprisoned American. The mission is seen as controversial, given the recent developments in North Korea, including a long-range rocket test and ongoing work at nuclear testing facilities, which might lead to a third nuclear bomb test. The delegation, including Schmidt's daughter and Google executive Jared Cohen, flew from Beijing to Pyongyang on North Korean state carrier Air Koryo. North Korean state news agency KCNA confirmed their arrival but provided no further details. The mission has drawn criticism from the White House due to the sensitive timing, as the U.S. does not have diplomatic relations with North Korea, and the country remains technically at war with South Korea. South Korea is also in a period of political transition, with a new President set to take office in February.",International News,2013-01-08 00:00:00
