ael has maintained that a rocket launched by the Palestinian Islamic Jihad had misfired and landed on the hospital, resulting in casualties. A day earlier, Modi had reacted to the Gaza hospital incident. “Deeply shocked at the tragic loss of lives at the Al Ahli Hospital in Gaza. Our heartfelt condolences to the families of the victims, and prayers for speedy recovery of those injured.His remarks were in line with the statement earlier by the Ministry of External Affairs whose spokesperson Arindam Bagchi said there was an universal obligation to observe international humanitarian law, and also a global responsibility to fight the menace of terrorism in all its forms and manifestations. Modi’s call to Abbas came days after he spoke to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to extend solidarity. On October 10, Modi thanked Netanyahu “for his phone call and providing an update on the ongoing situation” and said “people of India stand in solidarity with Israel in this difficult hour”.",National News,2023-10-19 00:00:00
RRI scientists find new approach to explore nature of cold dark matter,"Bengaluru: Scientists from the Bengaluru-based Raman Research Institute (RRI) have found a new approach to explore the nature of cold dark matter (CDM), an elusive form of matter believed to make up 25% of the universe. In a recently published study, RRI professor Shiv Sethi and his collaborator Abineet Parichha demonstrated that weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) remain a promising candidate for CDM if certain assumptions about their stability are relaxed. Previously, models from particle physics that predicted stable WIMPs were at odds with cosmological models and experimental constraints regarding dark matter interactions. By considering unstable WIMPs that decay into particles, including a component that serves as CDM in the late universe, the researchers expanded the range of allowed WIMP properties. “We found that the WIMP model is still viable under the relaxed assumptions. In addition, data from the James Webb Space Telescope might reveal more exciting possibilities in the dark matter sector,” Prof Sethi, a senior astronomer at RRI, an autonomous institute of the department of science and technology (DST), said. The nature of both dark matter and dark energy has long perplexed scientists, DST said, adding that if confirmed, this new approach of looking for particle decay signatures could provide vital clues into the composition of the predominant matter in the universe. “Upcoming precise measurements of cosmic microwave background radiation and high-redshift neutral hydrogen distributions may help corroborate the unstable cold dark matter hypothesis. More observations and theoretical advances will be needed to unravel the mysteries that lurk unseen throughout the cosmos,” DST said.","Scientists from Raman Research Institute in Bengaluru proposed a new approach to study cold dark matter (CDM), constituting 25% of the universe. By relaxing assumptions about weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) stability, they found WIMPs remain a viable CDM candidate, offering insights into the universe's composition. Further research and observations are warranted.",Science and Technology,2024-01-15 00:00:00
