"Nexus One could leave Apple, Nokia sweating","NEW DELHI: Google's Nexus One mobile phone is set to challenge existing smartphone makers, including Apple and Nokia in India, helped by lower price points and rich features. The phone is currently available in the UK, Hong Kong and Singapore, apart from the US. Indian consumers may have to wait longer to be able to buy Nexus One. “We want to gradually roll out the Nexus One in different countries. It will ensure that the ordering process works smoothly and also help us gain feedback . We also wanted to ensure that the import regulations didn’t make the phone prohibitively expensive,” said a Google spokesperson, when asked about the phone’s availability in India. Nexus One is priced at $529, and can be unlocked from any GSM carrier. Google is also offering the phone for $179, with a two-year contract from TMobile . Thus, technically speaking the imported device will be available in Indian market, within a few weeks, through unofficial channel. At $529, (Rs 24,330), the smartphone is cheaper than the Apple’s iPhone available at Rs 30,000. The iPhone 3G though not available as yet, will cost upwards of Rs 40,000, when its US price is converted in Indian rupees. “We hope to allow people in other countries to purchase the Nexus One and future phones from Google soon,” the Google spokesperson added. Nexus One is definitely a feature rich phone. It comes with a 5 megapixel auto focus with flash and 4GB SD card, which can be further be expanded to 32 GB. Nexus One also introduces a voice-enabled keyboard for all text fields. One can speak a text message, tweet, or update Facebook, or an email, via voice. It can also search Google, call contacts, or get driving directions by just speaking into the phone. Google terms its phone as a superphone. “The Nexus One belongs to the emerging class of devices, which we call ‘superphones,’ with the 1GHz Qualcomm Snapdragon chipset making it as powerful as your laptop computer of three to four years ago,” said Andy Rubin , VP of engineering at Google. The company plans to bring more Android phones to the market, he added. US analysts expect Google’s mobile ad revenue of $75 million to grow 100% annually, because of better control over the Android and mobile search environment. “Google is now functioning more like a hardware OEM, although it calls itself a “merchant” . Because the Nexus One can be unlocked from any carrier, the GSM-based handset is likely to compete with the Apple iPhone,” says Malindi Davies of US-based SFG Fundamental Research.","Google's Nexus One smartphone is set to challenge Apple and Nokia in India with its lower price and advanced features. Priced at $529, it's more affordable than the iPhone, positioned to compete at Rs 24,330 compared to the iPhone's Rs 30,000. While currently available in the UK, Hong Kong, and Singapore, its Indian launch is delayed due to a gradual rollout strategy. The Nexus One introduces features like a 5-megapixel camera and a voice-enabled keyboard, part of Google's plan to expand its presence in the smartphone market.",Technology and Gadgets,2010-01-07 00:00:00
