Security concerns delay FM-III rollout,"NEW DELHI: The much awaited rollout of the third phase of FM radio is likely get further delayed with the defence ministry raising some security issues pertaining to ‘‘sensitivities'' of the rollout in the border areas.FM-III is expected to throw up about 800 new radio stations in small towns with a special focus on border areas of J&K and Northeast. The proposal has been pending before the Union Cabinet for some time now. According to I&B ministry sources the defence ministry has made certain suggestions about the rollout. ‘‘There are certain issues raised by the defence ministry. We hope these will be taken up in a meeting with the Cabinet Secretariat soon,'' a ministry source said. While maintaining that it was ‘‘fully supportive'' of the new policy, the defence ministry (MoD) said it had only suggested ‘‘some steps'' which should be taken into consideration for the FM transmitters. For one thing, MoD wants that the frequency distribution should be allocated in consultation with it since the armed forces also use different types of communication equipment in the border areas. ‘‘The working of their equipment should not be disturbed,'' said an official. For another, the ‘‘content or programme development'' should also take ‘‘inputs'' from the armed forces because of ‘‘their large-scale involvement'' in the forward areas. ‘‘The Army, for instance, has been running ‘‘Operation Sadbhavana'' in J&K — an initiative that aims to help rebuild the socio-economic life of people hit by terrorism. Such initiatives should also be reflected in the programmes, which should not be merely restricted to Bollywood songs,'' he added. MoD has also rejected the proposal that armed forces should provide security to the transmitters and stations. ‘‘Armed forces do not provide security to static civilian installations. For such duties, there are other forces like CISF,'' he said. The I&B ministry has been keen on pushing the policy and has even incentivised the entry of private channels by cutting down infrastructure costs by 50%.","The rollout of FM radio's third phase in India, aiming to bring stations to underserved areas including border regions, is facing delays due to security concerns raised by the Defense Ministry. The Issue: The Defense Ministry is concerned about potential interference with military communication equipment in border areas like J&K and the Northeast. Defense Ministry's Suggestions: They propose joint frequency allocation with the ministry to avoid disruption. Content development should consider military initiatives like ""Operation Sadbhavana"" to better serve border communities. Security for radio stations should be handled by civilian forces, not the military. Current Status: I&B Ministry, while supportive of the expansion, is awaiting a meeting with the Cabinet Secretariat to address the Defense Ministry's concerns. The rollout, which aims for 800 new stations in small towns, has been stalled due to these discussions.",Technology and Gadgets,2010-05-08 00:00:00
