ence, ekbote claimed that they not only personally defamed him but they maligned brahmins as a community. ekbote''s brother, g r ekbote, who is chairman, progressive education society (pes), alleged the pamphlets also contained defamatory material against pes, its board members.","The president of the Bharatiya Janata Party's (BJP) city unit in Pune, Anil Shirole, who is contesting the upcoming civic polls, along with three BJP activists, has been booked by the Deccan Gymkhana police for distributing defamatory pamphlets against a rival candidate. The complaint led to charges under sections 123 and 127 of the People's Representative Act and section 171-G of the Indian Penal Code. Shirole denied the charges, labeling them as a conspiracy by his rivals to confuse his supporters, emphasizing that he was unaware of the activities of the accused activists in his panel. One of the activists, Ashok Lokhande, was released on bail after appearing before the Judicial Magistrate First Class (JMFC). An independent candidate from the same panel, Milind Ekbote, claimed that he and his supporters caught BJP activists red-handed distributing defamatory pamphlets against him on Ghole Road. Ekbote alleged that the car used for distributing pamphlets belonged to Shirole, accusing the BJP activists not only of personal defamation but also of maligning the Brahmin community. The pamphlets reportedly contained defamatory material against the Progressive Education Society (PES) and its board members. Ekbote's brother, G. R. Ekbote, who is the chairman of PES, echoed these allegations. The incident adds tension and controversy to the civic poll campaign in Pune.",Politics,2002-02-10 00:00:00
