This is the best honour I could get: Asha Parekh on receiving Dadasaheb Phalke award,"New Delhi: Veteran actor Asha Parekh was Friday honoured with the Dada Saheb Phalke award. It is the highest recognition in the field of Indian cinema. Asha Parekh, 79, was presented the award by President Droupadi Murmu during the 68th National Film Awards ceremony, held at Vigyan Bhawan here. The veteran said she is grateful to receive the prestigious award a day before her 80th birthday. “It is a huge honour to have received the Dada Saheb Phalke award. It makes me very grateful that the recognition comes to me just one day before my 80th birthday,” Asha Parekh said. “This is the best honour I could get from the Government of India. I would like to thank the jury for the recognition that they have bestowed upon me, my long journey and fulfilling the journey in the film industry,” said Parekh. She is the recipient of the award for the year 2020. Parekh described the Indian film industry as the ‘best place’ to be in. The actor said she continues to be attached to the movies in her own small way even after 60 years. “Our film industry is the best place to be in. And I would like to suggest to the youngsters who are in this industry to have perseverance, determination, discipline, and to be grounded, and I congratulate all the awardees tonight,” Parekh stated. Congratulating the cinema icon, the president said the award for Parekh is also an honour for the ‘indomitable female power’. “I congratulate all the winners at the 68th National Film Awards. I offer my special congratulations to Asha Parekh ji, the recipient of the Dada Saheb Phalke award. Our sisters of her generation made their mark in various fields despite many constraints. Honour to Ms Parekh is also an honour for the indomitable female power,” Murmu said. The five-member Dada Saheb Phalke Award committee – comprising Asha Bhosle, Hema Malini, Poonam Dhillon, Udit Narayan, and TS Nagabharana – selected Parekh for the honour. Information & Broadcasting Minister Anurag Thakur said Parekh motivated many women to follow their dreams. “Devika Rani ji was the first winner of the Dada Saheb Phalke award in 1969. And today it is being awarded to Asha Parekh, an actress who entertained not just Indian but global audience for decades. She took Indian culture to the corners of the world. Asha ji, you motivated so many women to step forward and participate in cinema and other various fields,” Thakur said. Parekh’s stardom was at par with male contemporaries Rajesh Khanna, Rajendra Kumar, Dharmendra and Manoj Kumar in the 1960s-1970s. She started her acting career at the age of 10 with the 1952 film Aasmaan. In a career spanning over five decades, Asha Parekh starred in over 95 films that include hits like Dil Deke Dekho, Kati Patang, Teesri Manzil, Baharon Ke Sapne, Pyar Ka Mausam, and Caravan. Parekh made her debut as a leading lady in Nasir Hussain’s 1959 movie Dil Deke Dekho, opposite Shammi Kapoor. Parekh was also honoured with the Padma Shri, the fourth-highest civilian award of the country, in 1992. Last year, the Dadasaheb Phalke Award for 2019 was conferred on Rajinikanth.","Veteran actor Asha Parekh received the prestigious Dada Saheb Phalke award, the highest recognition in Indian cinema, at the 68th National Film Awards ceremony. Parekh expressed gratitude for the honor, coinciding with her 80th birthday, and emphasized the importance of perseverance and determination in the film industry. The award recognizes her significant contributions to cinema over her illustrious 60-year career.",Entertainment,2022-09-30 00:00:00
"APWWS alleges violation of APSCW rules, seeks govt’s intervention","Alleging ‘gross violation’ of the rules of the APSCW Act, 2002, in the recent formation of the 5th Arunachal Pradesh State Commission for Women (APSCW), the Arunachal Pradesh Women’s Welfare Society (APWWS) has sought immediate intervention of the state government in the matter. In a release on Saturday, the APWWS stated, ‘As per information, the government has appointed non-APST persons who are outside the panel list prepared by the preceding Commission, which is complete violation of Section 5(1) and Section 5(5) of the APSCW Act 2002.’ Citing the provisions of the Act, the APWWS said all the members of the APSCW are to be APST women, and that ‘for the purpose of constitution of subsequent Commission in the state, the panel of candidates shall be prepared by the precedingCommission.’ Expressing grave concern over the issue, the APWWS stated that it is not against any individual and does not question the credentials and capabilities of the appointed members, but that it is concerned over the gross violation of the laid down rules for appointment under the APSCW Act, 2002. ‘No agency should undermine the very purpose of establishment of the APSCW and its motto to achieve the desired goal,’ the APWWS release added.","The Arunachal Pradesh Women's Welfare Society (APWWS) has raised concerns about the alleged ""gross violation"" of the rules of the Arunachal Pradesh State Commission for Women (APSCW) Act, 2002, in the recent formation of the 5th APSCW. The APWWS claims that non-APST (Arunachal Pradesh Scheduled Tribe) individuals were appointed, contrary to the Act's provisions, which require all members of the APSCW to be APST women. The APWWS calls for the state government's immediate intervention to address the alleged violation.",Crime and Justice,2018-03-25 00:00:00
