 dancing helps in improving your core balance and overall strength and helps in tightening your leg muscles and butt muscles. While holistic health guru Mickey Mehta states that ballroom dancing is a good cardio exercise and can be done between other exercises as a stress relieving activity to complement your regular fitness regime. Fitness instructor Bhavna Harchandraai further adds that dancing also gives a fillip to your neuro-muscular coordination.Ballroom dancing consists of 10 dances5 latin dances: Rumba, Samba, Jive, Cha Cha, Paso Doble5 Standard Dances: Foxtrot, Quickstep, Waltz, Viennese Waltz, Tango","This article promotes ballroom dancing as a fun and effective way to get fit. It compares ballroom dancing to the gym and emphasizes it is a celebrity favorite. The passage lists different types of ballroom dances and quotes health professionals on the benefits of ballroom dancing including improved heart health, stress reduction, and muscle toning",Health and Wellness,2010-02-06 00:00:00
Spain makes face masks mandatory in hospitals and clinics after a spike in respiratory illnesses,"Face masks will be mandatory in hospitals and healthcare centres in Spain starting on Wednesday due to a surge in respiratory illnesses, the Health Ministry said. The new leftist minority coalition government is imposing the measure despite opposition from most of Spain’s 17 autonomous regions. “We are talking about putting on a mask when you enter a health centre and taking it off when you leave,” Health Minister Mónica García told Cadena Ser radio late Monday. “I don’t think it is any drama. It is a basic and simple measure of the first order,” she added.Spain’s hospitals have come under immense pressure in recent weeks following a spike in cases of flu,COVID-19and other respiratory illnesses. García’s ministry decided to impose the measure after failing to reach an agreement with regional health authorities, many of whom argued that mask use should be recommended but not obligatory. Regional governments are in charge of healthcare although the central government can intervene if it deems it necessary. Six regions have already introduced the measure and masks have been commonly used on streets and public transport and in health centres in recent months. Spain declared a formal end to the health crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic last July, saying people no longer needed to wear masks in health and care centres and pharmacies. Over the previous two years, Spain had gradually ended mandatory mask wearing, first in public and then on public transport. The country registered more than 14 million cases and some 120,000 deaths from thecoronavirus.","Starting Wednesday, all people visiting hospitals or healthcare centers in Spain will have to wear face masks due to a rise in respiratory illnesses despite resistance from most regions. Health Minister Mónica García emphasized the measure as vital and non-dramatic for everyone's safety amidst an increase in cases of flu, COVID-19 and other similar diseases that are stressing hospits over recent weeks. This directive is enforced by a central government after unsuccessful attempts to reach consensus with regional health authorities advocating voluntary mask use instead of mandatory compliance. Some regions have already adopted the measure while Spain had earlier declared an end to COVID-19 crisis in July 2023, stating that no longer required individuals to wear masks inside hospitals and pharmacies as well as on public transportation after two years since its outbreak peaked with over 14 million cases.",International News,2024-01-09 00:00:00
Railways spent Rs 98.10 to earn Rs 100 in 2022-23: Ashwini Vaishnaw,"Post Covid-19, Railways achieved the highest ever total revenue of 2,40,177 cr in 2022-23 with operating ratio of 98.10 per cent, Rajya Sabha was told. Railways Minister Ashwini Vaishnaw informed the house on Thursday that the railways spent Rs 98.10 to earn Rs 100 in 2022-23. Vaishnaw's answer came in response to a question raised by Jawhar Sircar, Rajya Sabha MP from the All India Trinamool Congress party, who asked, ""Whether the Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) of India has declared that finances of the Indian Railways have slipped into 'concern zone' in 2021-22."" Sircar asked the minister to provide a year-wise operating ratio of Railways over the last five years and whether Railways spent Rs 107 to earn Rs 100 in 2021-22. ""Whether it is a fact that if accounting adjustments like considering advances for next financial year as receipts are ignored, the ratio has stayed above 100 per cent since 2018-19,"" the Rajya Sabha MP also asked. In response, Vaishnaw stated that CAG in its report 13 of 2023 examined railways finances to the end of March 2022 and submitted its recommendations. ""Railway operations continued to be adversely impacted by the disruption induced by Covid-19 in 2021-22 also. Despite this Railways' achieved total receipts of 1,91,367 cr. against 1,40,783 cr. in 2020-21 i.e. incremental revenues of 50,584 cr,"" he said. ""Post Covid-19 period, Railways achieved the highest ever total revenue of 2,40,177 cr. in 2022-23 with operating ratio (OR) of 98.10%. The receipts including advances etc. are accounted for as per laid down policy,"" the minister added. The five-year data, provided by the minister, shows that the Railways spent Rs 97.30 in 2018-19, Rs 98.36 in 2019-2020, and Rs 97.45 in 2020-2021 to earn RS.100","Railways Minister Ashwini Vaishnaw informed the Rajya Sabha that post-Covid-19, Indian Railways achieved its highest-ever total revenue of INR 2,40,177 crore in the fiscal year 2022-23, with an operating ratio of 98.10%. Responding to a question about the Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) declaring Indian Railways' finances in the ""concern zone"" in 2021-22, Vaishnaw stated that despite the disruptions caused by Covid-19, the railways achieved incremental revenues of INR 50,584 crore in 2021-22. The operating ratio represents the percentage of expenses in relation to revenue, and a lower ratio is considered better.",Local News,2024-02-05 00:00:00
All court orders can now be challenged,"The new amendments to Code of Criminal Procedure -- that have been kept in abeyance for almost a year -- have also laid down procedures for the protection of rape victims seeking punishment for their tormentors. The code gives victims the right to appeal against a court order acquitting an accused, or convicting the accused of a lesser offence. Under the amended Section 372 of CrPC, the victim will not need the permission of any law enforcement or prosecuting agency to appeal a court order. Currently, an appeal can be made only if the prosecution so decides -- a lacuna which allows the rich and the powerful who can influence the prosecution to get away, literally, with murder.","The new amendments to the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC), pending implementation for nearly a year, establish procedures to protect rape victims seeking justice. Under the amended Section 372, victims can appeal court orders acquitting the accused or convicting them of lesser offenses without needing permission from law enforcement or prosecuting agencies. This change addresses a significant gap in the current system, which allows appeals only if the prosecution decides to do so. This loophole has enabled influential individuals to evade justice, effectively allowing them to escape punishment for serious crimes like murder.",Crime and Justice,2010-01-01 00:00:00
RBI: Banks to continue accepting scribbled notes,"Mumbai, December 31 Banks will continue to accept currency notes with scribbling, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) said today, dismissing rumours that it has stopped banks from accepting such notes from tomorrow. “In the wake of rumours circulating in the market that from January 1, 2014, banks will not accept banknotes with anything written on them, the RBI has urged members of public not to fall prey to such rumours and to use their banknotes without any fear,” the RBI said. The RBI said it had not issued any such instructions. However, it reiterated that writing or scribbling on banknotes works against its ‘clean note policy’ and sought co-operation from public, institutions and others in keeping the banknotes clean by not writing anything on them. Referring to its August instructions on the ‘clean note policy’, the RBI said banks were advised to instruct their staff not to scribble or write on the body of the banknotes. — PTI","The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) refuted circulating rumors that banks would stop accepting currency notes with writing from January 1, 2014. RBI clarified it hadn't issued any such instructions. However, it emphasized its 'clean note policy,' urging the public not to write on banknotes and requested cooperation in maintaining clean currency.",Business and Finance,2014-01-01 00:00:00
"Viru, Unmukt give Delhi good lead","Virender Sehwag is just a shadow of his past self now. The spectacles seem to have disturbed the famous hand-eye coordination he once was known for. The uninhibited swing of the bat and his disdain for the ball is still there to admire but the timing ditches him. His 64-run knock on Monday was full of mistimed shots but the ones that did connect evoked memories of the past. It wasn’t a flawless innings as the bowlers troubled Sehwag throughout his 90-ball stay in the middle. That there was ample assistance for the bowlers from the pitch and the weather made it an important innings for Delhi, who are looking to take maximum points from the game. Sehwag’s third wicket partnership of 128 runs with Unmukt Chand, who is unbeaten on 87, earned the hosts a crucial 60-run lead in the first innings as Delhi posted 201 for 3 on the second day of their Ranji Trophy match against Rajasthan at the Ferozeshah Kotla Stadium. For the second consecutive day, poor light robbed the day’s game of a good number of overs — 38 on Monday — as the morning session was completely lost to the fog. Upon resumption, Delhi lost night-watchman Varun Sood in the sixth over of the day with the addition of just 12 runs. It brought Sehwag and Unmukt together and they batted for the next 30 overs with a mix of caution and aggression. Initially, Sehwag looked a bit tentative, throwing his bat at every other ball and fishing outside the off-stump. A few edges flew past slips too but after spending a few overs at the crease, his batting started to look more and more compact and the shots that were betraying him at the start began to flow smoothly. Habits die hard, as they say, and Sehwag isn’t one to let anyone dictate the terms. living up to his name, he completed his half-century with a six over the bowler’s head. Amidst all this, Unmukt quietly built his innings playing second fiddle to his senior partner. In fact, Sehwag’s presence at the other end helped the former India U-19 captain. Sehwag’s aggression, as it used to do for his Indian team partners, eased the pressure on Unmukt. To his credit, Unmukt also batted well and never seemed bothered by the movement of the ball. Sehwag’s innings finally came to an end when he tried to pull a short-pitched delivery over mid-wicket. His departure didn’t affect the scoring rate as Mithun Manhas immediately took over the role of the aggressor and briskly scored 34 runs. As weather is expected to be foggy for the next couple of days, Delhi look to play the morning session on Tuesday and put Rajasthan in once again and try to earn maximum points from the match. Brief Scores Rajasthan: 141 (Rajesh Bishnoi 57, Aristh Singhvi 28; Parvinder Awana 2-15) trail Delhi: 201/3 in 56 overs (Unmukt Chand 87 batting, Virender Sehwag 64, Mithun Manhas 34 batting; Aniket Choudhary 2/23) by 60 runs.","Virender Sehwag's Ranji Trophy performance has been a mix of mistimed shots and glimpses of his past brilliance. Sehwag, who is now playing for Delhi, scored 64 runs in their match against Rajasthan, with a third-wicket partnership of 128 runs with Unmukt Chand. Despite his less-than-perfect innings, the partnership helped Delhi post a total of 201 for 3 on the second day, earning a crucial 60-run lead in the first innings. The weather conditions have affected the match, and with fog expected for the next couple of days, Delhi aims to play the morning session on Tuesday and put Rajasthan in once again.",Sports,2014-12-23 00:00:00
Consider plea against converting parking area into park: HC,"Madurai: Madras high court has directed the authorities to consider and pass orders on a plea seeking a direction to the executive officer of Kanyakumari special grade town panchayat to stop the proceedings to convert a two-wheeler parking area on the western side of Triangular Park, opposite Gandhi Mandapam, into a park. The court was hearing a public interest litigation filed by Manikandan. The petitioner's counsel submitted that the parking area itself is insufficient, and converting it into a park would cause huge traffic congestion in the area. A representation by the petitioner was also not considered. A division bench of justice M S Ramesh and justice A D Maria Clete observed that it is needless to point out that whenever a representation of this nature is made to a statutory authority, there is a duty cast upon them to consider the same on its own merits and pass appropriate orders in one way or another, instead of keeping it pending indefinitely. Non-consideration of the representation by the statutory authority would amount to dereliction of duty. The court will be justified in invoking its extraordinary powers under Article 226 of the Constitution and directing them to consider the same within a stipulated time. Hence, the judges directed the authorities to consider and pass orders on merits and in accordance with the law on the representation made by the petitioner within three months, after giving sufficient opportunity to all parties concerned. The petition was disposed of.","The Madras High Court has directed the authorities to review and pass a decision on a petition requesting the halt of converting a two-wheeler parking area near Triangular Park in Kanyakumari into a park. The petition, filed by Manikandan, argued that the parking area is already insufficient, and the proposed conversion would lead to significant traffic congestion. The court noted that authorities are obligated to consider such representations and pass appropriate orders within a reasonable time. It ordered that the authorities review the petition and make a decision within three months, providing an opportunity for all parties to be heard. The petition was disposed of.",Crime and Justice,2024-12-01 00:00:00
Ajay Devgn's high-octane action stunts in Tezz,"Ajay Devgn has done some thrilling action sequences in his upcoming release Tezz The promos of Priyadarshan’s slick thriller Tezz have created quite a buzz. Ajay Devgn and the rest of the cast have performed high-octane action stunts designed by Hollywood power duo Gareth Milne (Bourne Ultimatum and Bourne Identity) and Peter Pedrero (stunt co-ordinator of The Bourne Supremacy and a few action sequences from the Harry Potter series).The film also stars Anil Kapoor, Kangana Ranaut, Sameera Reddy and Zayed Khan, and has been produced by Ratan Jain. Says Devgn, “It’s a fabulous mix of international action and Indian emotions. Films work only if they connect with the audience, and Tezz has that emotional element. It has been presented in a very stylised manner with some fabulous action.” Peter Pedrero who has previously worked in some Indian films says, “Ajay has done a lot of his own stunts and was very focused. He is a very good student; when we demonstrated something, he would listen carefully and then within a couple of attempts perfect the shot. One day we were doing some test shots on a jet ski at very high speeds and close to the riverbank. Priyan asked me, ‘Do you think we could get Ajay to do something like that?’ Just as I was about to answer him, we looked over at the man doing the tests and did a double take. Who we thought was a stunt driver actually turned out to be Ajay!” Among the many thrilling action sequences in the film, Ajay and Anil have shot a hand-to-hand combat sequence in a tunnel. “Both actors are fantastic. We briefed them in detail about how trained their characters would be and then designed the fight around their capabilities. We wanted them to do all the fights themselves and not use body doubles, making it look more dramatic and believable,” Pedrero informs. The action director also says that the car, bike and helicopter chase sequences involving Devgn are very explosive. “We shot on busy streets in Birmingham and in Scotland. I would say the hardest and possibly the most dangerous stunt is when Sameera’s character slides her bike underneath a parked truck and safely emerges on the other side. All the action involving the vehicles was challenging.” Tezz is a Venus Worldwide Entertainment presentation and releases on April 27.","In the upcoming film ""Tezz,"" Ajay Devgn showcases thrilling action stunts crafted by Hollywood experts Gareth Milne and Peter Pedrero. Directed by Priyadarshan and produced by Ratan Jain, the movie also features Anil Kapoor, Kangana Ranaut, Sameera Reddy, and Zayed Khan. Devgn, praised for his commitment to performing his stunts, engages in intense hand-to-hand combat scenes with Kapoor. The film promises explosive chase sequences involving cars, bikes, and helicopters, shot in locations like Birmingham and Scotland. Scheduled for release on April 27, ""Tezz"" blends international action with Indian emotions for a captivating cinematic experience.",Entertainment,2012-01-28 00:00:00
