"The biggest tech trends to watch out for in 2021, from Fintech to E-Commerce","Technology to the Internet of Things, from the Internet of Things to the Cloud to the Smart Home, your shopping cart needs to change, according to a new report from KGI Securities. In a ""Smart Home"" report released Tuesday, KGI revealed that a number of its top selling product names and services, such as Home Shopping Cart, App Store, and even a subscription to KGI Online also had their growth spurt in the second quarter due to the launch of their products. On a list of top 20 ""Fintech"" services that KGI said they used to be the fastest growing, ""Visa, Bancorp, Visa, and MasterCard are on note but have now lost out or are on the precipice of a loss,"" KGI's report states. KGI also showed a sharp rise in a year-to-date year-end number of revenue, which resulted in $6.3 billion in revenue growth in 2016, a 20 percent increase over the year-ago peak. KGI's report goes on to highlight other promising new services, which it highlighted earlier this year, including a new ""Smart Home"" service for the first time in four years that will feature a home entertainment system built into the device. ""Fintech has its own way"" at the top of the list, KGI report says, and now it will ""continue expanding its customer base of IoT in the form of its 'Smart Home' initiative,"" adding that ""the overall U.S. economy has been built more on a personal experience, with more business investment than on a digital product."" The report said that the U.S. economy grew by nearly 4 percent between 2001 and 2015, with the exception of that year, when gross domestic product contracted, and the consumer spending, which is now growing, grew over the same period. If KGI's report wasn't bad enough, it appears that other major tech firms and emerging technologies have also recently taken notice of KGI's report. Google Inc.'s $18.2 billion in revenue in the fourth quarter was an important shift in Google's business,