More beds for quarantine & isolation wards in Nashik,"NASHIK: The district administration and Nashik Municipal Corporation (NMC) on Wednesday jointly decided to substantially increase the number of beds in the isolation and quarantine wards. While the number of the beds for isolation has been increased from 16 to 76, a total of 78 beds have been kept ready for quarantine. Although no positive case of Covid-19 has been reported in the city, the district and civic administrations are taking every measure to monitor situation in case the number of suspects increases. Nashik district collector Suraj Mandhare, municipal commissioner Radhakrishna Game and district civil surgeon Suresh Jagdale on Wednesday inspected some of the hospitals and municipal corporation buildings to review the arrangements of beds for isolation and quarantine. Mandhare and Game also took review of the arrangements of isolation and quarantine of Covid-19 with district civil surgeon and health officials during a meeting held after the visit. “Travellers coming from 10 most-affected countries like Dubai, UK, France, Germany, Dubai, Iran and Italy are to be quarantined in the hospitals, while those coming from other countries are to be quarantined in their homes,” Jagdale said, adding the positive patients are to be treated in the quarantine wards. Apart from the existing 16 beds for isolation in district civil hospital, arrangement of 60 more beds have been made at Dr Zakir Hussain hospital and other private hospitals. There will be 40 beds for quarantine at Dr Zakir Hussain hospital, while arrangements of remaining 38 beds have been done at six private hospitals. Meanwhile, the NMC has started spraying anti-biotic in public places across the city as part of preventive measures. The civic administration has started spraying of anti-biotic on experimental basis at Rajiv Gandhi Bhavan — headquarters of NMC, Central Bus Stand and district collectorate. The spraying was done on floor, railings, office tables and chairs.","The Nashik district administration and Nashik Municipal Corporation (NMC) have increased the number of beds for Covid-19 isolation from 16 to 76 and prepared 78 quarantine beds across hospitals. While no positive cases have been reported, authorities are taking proactive measures, including inspections by District Collector Suraj Mandhare and Municipal Commissioner Radhakrishna Game. Travelers from high-risk countries are quarantined in hospitals, while others are monitored at home. Additional isolation beds are arranged at Dr. Zakir Hussain Hospital and private facilities. The NMC has also initiated experimental antibiotic spraying in public places to prevent the virus's spread",Health and Wellness,2020-03-19 00:00:00
"‘I dont like to show off,I like to tell a story’","For 12 years,Milan Luthria was one of many filmmakers crowding the margins of Bollywood,a director who cut his teeth on the chaos and camaraderie of Mahesh Bhatts film sets,and who went on to make competent formula films that drew crowds to single screens in the Hindi heartland. There have been more downs than ups in his career. He started with the success of Kachche Dhaage (1999),followed it up with the well-intentioned but cold Chori Chori (2003),went completely off-track with Deewaar (2004),showed edgy promise with Taxi No. 9211 (2006),and again went into oblivion with Hattrick (2007). Things changed with Once Upon a Time in Mumbaai (2010),a film on Mumbai don Haji Mastaan that successfully tapped the larger-than-life sensibility of Seventies Bollywood,and got both critics and front-benchers interested. But it is with the story of Silk in The Dirty Picture that the 44-year-old has truly arrived. Hes just won the Best Director award at the 18th Annual Colors Screen Awards. In this interview,he dissects his biggest hit,talks about meeting Silk Smitha and directing Vidya Balan. Excerpts:Is it true that you have interacted with Silk Smitha?I wouldnt go so far to say we interacted but I did meet her. She was shooting for a song in Mahesh Bhatts Naaraaz,which ended up being deleted. I was an assistant director in the film. No interaction was possible with her because she had reached a very hollow place. One could see that she was living in a cloud. When you talked to Silk Smitha,you realised that nobody was there. She had a team of people to convey our instructions to her. She was wonderful at her job but once the camera was off,she was a different person.Now that the film has made big money,had an impact and also won awards,what pleased you most about The Dirty Picture? And what is it that you wish you had done differently?Im pleased with the fact that I was able to achieve the balance between sexuality and emotion. It was a tightrope walk for a year.I had promised Vidya (Balan) that people would enjoy the sensual and sexual aspect and leave the theatre with awe and respect for her. I told Vidya that this film would be screened in her memory the day she dies.As a director,it was tough to get respect for a sexy subject. I was clear that I wasnt making a sex romp but telling the story of a sex object,who behind all her bravado,is a human being craving for emotional and familial acceptance.As for the negatives,its impossible not to look back and cringe. I cant watch my work. I can spot a thousand mistakes. Eventually,every filmmaker comes to the realisation that we are all flawed and so are our movies.When Vidya won the Best Actress trophy at the 18th Annual Colors Screen Awards,she said she was perplexed that you thought she could play Silk. She said,I dont know what was going on in Milans mind. Care to tell us what?(Laughs) Vidya is the classic voluptuous Indian beauty. I dont know why the Indian film industry didnt wake up to her before. She has shades of Hema Malini,Vyjayanthimala,Sridevi and Madhuri Dixit. Vidya is a complete Indian package. I felt that since she hasnt done something like this before,people would enjoy her in the role. Also since shes a south Indian,she fit the bill. She was my first and only choice.Even though The Dirty Picture is a womans story,it is told from a male gaze. Dont you think the emphasis on the skin show and the titillation defeats the purpose?I get the point youre making but let me say that I decided to explore and not exploit. The male gaze in the film is one of a caress and not carnage. The male gaze says its okay to embrace the lust in your mind and not to be afraid of it. The whole point is that the male gaze on a female is not bad,its sensual and not dirty. Its natural and erotic. One of the reasons to make this film was to bring the male gaze out of the closet. Nothing that we have shown in the film is not part of everyday life orgasms,S & M,sex with multiple partners it’s all part of life. We didnt want the men to watch the film alone. It was my conviction that the women would make the film a blockbuster and thats what has happened.Vidya told me that on the very first day you asked her to shoot the orgasm scene.Yes,I had to push her to the deep end from the beginning. I had to know if she would sink or swim. I thought we should know from day one rather than shoot for 10 weeks and then realise she couldnt go through with the role. I thought she would run away but she was brave.What was the most difficult scene that you shot with her?Where she ends up in the porn filmmakers studio. By then we had fallen in love with the character and,emotionally,it was difficult to see her go through this. It took a lot out of us to shoot the scene. I was very protective of Vidya when we were shooting it. Even when I was watching it,I felt awful,which made me realise that we are doing something right. I wanted this to be the audiences reaction too.From a director of films for men to a womans director,how would you describe your transition?I was getting sick of friends asking me why I always made guy films. As a filmmaker,you realise that scripts choose you. But I did have a desire to explore a womans story. Not a boring weepie,but a pulsating story of a woman. People around me said that I was taking a risk by stepping out of my comfort zone,my formula. (I thought) The Dirty Picture was waiting to be made.Once Upon a Time in Mumbaai,The Dirty Picture and now the sequel to Once Upon…,what is the secret of your chemistry with producer Ekta Kapoor?Theres a lot of mutual respect. I see Ekta as a courageous producer. Her strength lies in marketing and whenever I need a sounding board,shes available. Shes a full-on creative producer,not just a money person. She occupies the marketing zone while I stay in the creative. She doesnt get into my space and vice-versa.Youve been making movies for over 12 years but it’s only now that recognition has come your way. Why do you think youve been such a late bloomer?When I started,the trend was to segregate Bombay-centric films and the heartland films. Somehow,directors like Ram Gopal Varma and Karan Johar,who made the Bombay-centric films,got more recognition. Films that clicked in the heartland,like Kachche Dhaage,made money but they were not celebrated. My own record has been a bit of a see-saw. Chori Chori was bogged down by too many problems. Deewaar came after LoC and Lakshya when people were not in a mood to see a war film. Since then,its been a gradual upward graph. Taxi No. 9211 gave me critical and commercial acclaim and its gone well from there on. I guess it happens when it has to. Im grateful I was busy throughout.Do you remember the first time you said to yourself that you wanted to be a director?Yes,after a chance meeting with Mahesh Bhatt. I went on to assist him in Gumraah. After a few days,he asked me to go on the sets and put up the first shot. I was petrified. But I did it and realised that I had a wonderful time. I loved looking through the camera. I felt I had found my happy place.Describe yourself as a filmmaker in a line.Im a hardcore commercial filmmaker.What ingredients make a hardcore commercial film,in your book?Drama,dialogues,beautiful women,larger-than-life heroes and a pacy narrative. I dont like to show off that I know filmmaking,I like to tell the story.How much of Mahesh Bhatt is in you?Ive taken three things from him: economics,people management and pushing actors to their limits. He also taught me to be self-sufficient. I dont get fazed by problems on the sets. Like him,I also feel that the best part of making movies is the camaraderie on a set. Hes still my guru. He is with me to check the audience reaction,on the first day,first show,and hes the first one to whistle.Government allows online cab aggregators like Uber, Ola, and Rapido to charge up to two times the base fare during peak hours, with a minimum of 50% base fare during non-peak hours. States have been advised to adopt the revised guidelines within three months. Drivers to receive at least 80% of fare, while cancellation by drivers or passengers without valid reason will result in a penalty.","Milan Luthria, a Bollywood filmmaker, has experienced a fluctuating career over the past 12 years, marked by both successes and failures. He began with the hit ""Kachche Dhaage"" (1999) but faced challenges with subsequent films until ""Once Upon a Time in Mumbaai"" (2010) revived his standing in the industry. His most significant achievement came with ""The Dirty Picture,"" which tells the story of actress Silk Smitha and earned him the Best Director award at the 18th Annual Colors Screen Awards. In an interview, Luthria reflected on his brief encounter with Smitha, describing her as a complex person who was different off-screen. He expressed satisfaction with balancing themes of sexuality and emotion in ""The Dirty Picture,"" highlighting the film's commercial success and critical acclaim.",Entertainment,2012-01-29 00:00:00
Told Canada it’s not Govt of India policy: Jaishankar on killing of separatist Nijjar,"In his first remarks on the row over Canada Prime Minister Justin Trudeau’s allegation of a potential Indian link to the killing of Khalistan separatist Hardeep Singh Nijjar, External Affairs Minister S Jaishankar said Wednesday that the government had told Ottawa that “this is not the Government of India’s policy”. Responding to a question on the Canadian allegation during an interaction at the Council on Foreign Relations in New York, Jaishankar said, “Yes, I do have a comment. I will share with you very frankly what we told the Canadians. One, we told the Canadians that this is not the Government of India’s policy. Two, we told the Canadians that look, if you have something specific, if you have something relevant, let us know. We are open to looking at it.”A day earlier, speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Jaishankar said “political convenience” should not be allowed to determine a country’s response to “terrorism, extremism and violence” — remarks construed as a veiled message to Canada and its Prime Minister. Targeting “rule-makers”, Jaishankar said that “respect for territorial integrity and non-interference in internal affairs cannot be exercises in cherry-picking” – a reference to Trudeau’s statement that any involvement of a foreign government in the killing of a Canadian citizen on Canadian soil was an “unacceptable violation of our sovereignty”.While Jaishankar’s comments have also been perceived as directed at Pakistan and China, the reference to “rule-makers” points to Canada which is part of the G7 grouping and exercises influence because of its close alliance with the US. While these were his first remarks on the India-Canada row, he framed it in the context of a global rules-based order. He also underlined that “the days when a few nations set the agenda and expected others to fall in line are over”.","Indian External Affairs Minister S. Jaishankar has addressed the recent controversy surrounding Canada Prime Minister Justin Trudeau's allegation of a potential Indian link to the killing of Khalistan separatist Hardeep Singh Nijjar. Jaishankar stated that the Indian government informed Canada that such allegations do not represent India's policy and urged Canada to provide specific and relevant information if they have any. He emphasized that ""political convenience"" should not dictate a country's response to terrorism and violence, indirectly referencing Canada's stance. Jaishankar's remarks were made within the context of a global rules-based order, signaling that nations should respect territorial integrity and non-interference in internal affairs.",Miscellaneous,2023-09-27 00:00:00
