Rupee up 22 paise to 48.50 a dollar,"The Indian rupee strengthened by 22 paise at 48.50 in opening trade on Monday on expectations of increased foreign fund inflows as stock markets may open higher in tandem with firming trends on the other Asian equity markets. However, dollars' demand from importers capped rupee's gains to some extent. At the Interbank Foreign Exchange (Forex) market, the domestic unit was quoted higher at 48.50 a dollar, a gain of 22 paise over the previous close of 48.72/73. Rupee weakened by 6 paise on Friday despite the firm equity markets. Meanwhile, the BSE Sensex ended 494.67 points, or 3.47 percent higher on Friday, while Hong Kong's Hang Seng index was up 2.25 percent in morning trade today.","The Indian rupee strengthened by 22 paise to 48.50 in the opening trade on Monday due to expectations of increased foreign fund inflows. This optimism was driven by the anticipation of higher opening stock markets in line with positive trends in other Asian equity markets. However, the rupee's gains were limited by a demand for dollars from importers. The domestic unit was quoted at 48.50 per dollar in the Interbank Foreign Exchange (Forex) market, marking a 22 paise gain compared to the previous close of 48.72/73. Despite firm equity markets, the rupee had weakened by 6 paise on the preceding Friday. The BSE Sensex had closed 494.67 points, or 3.47 percent higher on Friday, while Hong Kong's Hang Seng index was up 2.25 percent in morning trading on Monday.",Business and Finance,2009-07-20 00:00:00
