BackBack Narendra Modi releases 100 secret files on Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose,"New Delhi: Prime Minister Narendra Modi on Saturday released the first set of 100 digitised files relating to Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose in the public domain, the freedom icon who created the Indian National Army to throw off the shackles of British colonial rule in India. The declassification of the documents is widely expected to reveal the truth behind the disappearance of Bose seven decades ago. Saturday also happens to be the 119th birth anniversary of Bose. Modi also met family members of Netaji, including Prof. Chitra Ghosh, Shri Chandra Bose, and Shri Surya Kumar Bose, a government statement said. Two commissions of inquiry had concluded that Bose died in a plane crash in Taipei on 18 August 1945. A third commission of inquiry and many people, including some of his relatives, have contested that theory. Modi had, in his meeting with members of the Bose family in October, conveyed to them that the government would declassify the files relating to the leader. “There are some 33 files which the prime minister’s office had in its possession related to Netaji and these have been transferred to the National Archives. Different ministries of the government were also told to transfer whatever files they had in their possession to the National Archives"" said an official adding the number of files released were about 100. “Remembering Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose on his birth anniversary. His bravery & patriotism endears him to several Indians across generations,"" Modi said earlier in a post on Twitter. “Today is a special day for all Indians. Declassification of Netaji files starts today. Will go to National Archives myself for the same,"" he said in another post. There are some other theories about Netaji’s disappearance, one of them being that the leader fled to the former Soviet Union to continue to fight for India’s independence but was later killed. The other says that Netaji returned to India as an ascetic, ‘Gumnami Baba’, and continued to live in Uttar Pradesh’s Faizabad till 1985. Netaji’s daughter Anita Bose Pfaff, who currently lives in Germany, however believes that her father had died in the Taipei plane crash of 1945. In an interview published in the Hindustan Times on Friday, Pfaff said that her “personal belief"" was that her father “died in the plane crash."" A museum in Kolkata dedicated to Bose preserves memories of the leader. Its walls are lined with black and white photos of Bose’s parents, of him as a young boy, his May 1942 meeting with Germany’s then leader Adolf Hitler in Berlin and a picture of his German wife, Emilie Schenkl, holding baby Anita. Other pictures capture his 90-day journey from Germany to Japan aboard a submarine between February and May 1943. Another is allegedly the last known picture of Bose, in which he is seen stepping off a plane in Saigon on 17 August 1945, a day before his widely disputed death in an aircrash in Taipei.","On 23 January, 119 years to the day after the birth of one of India’s national heroes, the country’s prime minister, Narendra Modi, released the first batch of 33 digitised files relating to the life of Subhas Chandra Bose. Two further batches are due to be released in due course and it is expected that Bose’s family will call for a public investigation of the files as they suspect foul play in the leader’s 1945 death. The files are held at the national archives in the capital and in Calcutta, but the majority are held in the national archives in Delhi where the campaign for the files’ release has been the most vociferous.",National News,2016-01-23 00:00:00
Govt pulls out all stops to ensure NRG participation,"The entire state machinery has been mobilised to ensure maximum participation from non-resident Gujaratis NRGs) to participate in the Vishwa Gujarati Parivar Mahotsav, to be opened by Prime Minister A B Vajpayee, on Tuesday in Ahmedabad. Official sources said that nearly 4,000 NRGs have confirmed their arrival. Collectors of Anand, Kheda, Vadodara and Ahmedabad have been trying hard to seek another 1,000 confirmations.Nearly 90 state-sponsored private buses will picking up the NRGs to be brought to the venue straight from the districts. The rest may come on their own. All top bureaucrats, including chiefs of PSUs, have been given specific tasks to organise the Ahmedabad function. ""Most of the NRGs who are expected here are already in Gujarat for social functions, one reason why the task of the state officials to involve them in the largely-attended show has become very easy,"" confided a senior official. The prime minister would be releasing two books, ''Vatan ni Vate â€” NRG''s Contribution to Gujarat'' and ''Beyond Boundaries'', both Times of India presentations. ''Vatan ni Vate'' carries the names and addresses of nearly 3,500 NRGs who have helped the state in different fields, starting with checkdams and water works, schools and educational institutions, to charitable hospitals and temples. ''Beyond Boundaries'', written by top historian Makrand Mehta, shows how, since the Harappan age, the Gujaratis established trade links with foreign countries. If agates were exported from Lothal 5000 years ago, then traders Satyaplan and Vastupal contributed in building the famous Delvada temples near Mt Abu in 8th century. The PM, who will felicitate five prominent NRGs, will also welcome three top experts â€” Skye Morrison, who will be presenting her Canadian stamps collection having kites printed on each; Bhanubhai Shah, who has been running a kites museum for the last 48 years in Ahmedabad; and 80-year-old Rasul Chacha, the oldest kite manufacturer who will be presenting his rare kite makes to the PM. Before the NRG meet, there will be three seminars on ''Water and energy'', ''Emerging technologies'' and ''Tourism and the Gujarati diaspora''. The participants include Bhishma Agnihotri, India''s ambassador-atlarge in the US, and NRGs from US, UK and Africa.","The state is actively engaging non-resident Gujaratis (NRGs) for the Vishwa Gujarati Parivar Mahotsav, to be inaugurated by Prime Minister A. B. Vajpayee in Ahmedabad. Nearly 4,000 NRGs have confirmed attendance, with efforts to secure another 1,000. Official buses will transport attendees, while top officials are coordinating the event. The PM will release two books highlighting NRG contributions and Gujarat's historical trade links. He will also honour prominent NRGs and welcome experts. Preceding the event, seminars on water, energy, technology, and tourism will take place, with participation from NRGs worldwide.",National News,2004-01-14 00:00:00
